# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:united-states/100th-meridian-west] The **meridian 100° west** of the Prime Meridian of Greenwich is a line of longitude that extends from the North Pole across the Arctic Ocean, North America, the Pacific Ocean, the Southern Ocean, and Antarctica to the South Pole.
[src:united-states/100th-meridian-west] The 100th meridian west forms a great circle with the 80th meridian east.
[src:united-states/100th-meridian-west] In the United States, this meridian roughly marks the boundary between the semi-arid climate in the west and the humid continental and humid subtropical climates in the east, and as such roughly connotes the regions of the Eastern and the Western United States.
[src:united-states/100th-meridian-west] In the United States the meridian 100° west of Greenwich forms the eastern border of the Texas panhandle with Oklahoma (which traces its origin to the Adams-Onís Treaty in 1819 which settled the border between New Spain and the United States between the Red River and Arkansas River).
[src:united-states/100th-meridian-west] Dodge City, Kansas lies exactly at the intersection of the Arkansas River and the 100th meridian.
[src:united-states/100th-meridian-west] As first noted by John Wesley Powell in the 1870s, there is a big difference in rainfall by the different sides of the meridian.
[src:united-states/100th-meridian-west] West of the meridian, raising livestock is much more economically important than east of it, and what agriculture does exist relies heavily on irrigation.
[src:united-states/100th-meridian-west] Historically, the meridian has often been taken as a rough boundary between the eastern and western United States.
[src:united-states/100th-meridian-west] White settlement, spreading westward after the American Civil War, settled the area around this meridian during the 1870s.
[src:united-states/100th-meridian-west] Highway 30 in Cozad, Nebraska, marks the place where the 100th meridian intersects with the routes of the Oregon Trail, Pony Express, transcontinental railroad, and the Lincoln Highway.
[src:united-states/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] Presidential elections were held in the United States from December 15, 1788 to January 7, 1789, under the new Constitution ratified in 1788.
[src:united-states/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] George Washington was unanimously elected for the first of his two terms as president and John Adams became the first vice president.
[src:united-states/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] This was the only U.S. presidential election that spanned two calendar years without a contingent election and the first national presidential election in American history.
[src:united-states/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] Under the Articles of Confederation, which were ratified in 1781, the United States had no head of state.
[src:united-states/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] The executive function of government remained with the legislative similar to countries that use a parliamentary system.
[src:united-states/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] Federal power, strictly limited, was reserved to the Congress of the Confederation whose "President of the United States in Congress Assembled" was also chair of the Committee of the States which aimed to fulfill a function similar to that of the modern Cabinet.
[src:united-states/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] The Constitution created the offices of President and Vice President, fully separating these offices from Congress.
[src:united-states/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] The Constitution established an Electoral College, based on each state's congressional representation, in which each elector would cast two votes for two candidates, a procedure modified in 1804 by the ratification of the Twelfth Amendment.
[src:united-states/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] States had varying methods for choosing presidential electors.
[src:united-states/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] In five states, the state legislature chose electors.
[src:united-states/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] The other six chose electors through some form involving a popular vote, though in only two states did the choice depend directly on a statewide vote.
[src:united-states/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] The enormously popular Washington was distinguished as the former Commander of the Continental Army during the American Revolutionary War.
[src:united-states/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] After he agreed to come out of retirement, he was elected with ease unanimously; Washington did not select a running mate as that concept was not yet developed.
[src:united-states/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] No formal political parties existed, though an informally organized consistent difference of opinion had already manifested between Federalists and Anti-Federalists.
[src:united-states/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] Thus, the contest for the vice-presidency was open.
[src:united-states/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] Thomas Jefferson predicted that a popular Northern leader such as Governor John Hancock of Massachusetts or John Adams, a former minister to Great Britain who had represented Massachusetts in Congress, would be elected vice president.
[src:united-states/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] Anti-Federalists leaders such as Patrick Henry, who did not run, and George Clinton, who had opposed ratification of the Constitution, also represented potential choices.
[src:united-states/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] All 69 electors present cast one vote for Washington, making his election unanimous.
[src:united-states/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] Adams won 34 electoral votes and the vice presidency.
[src:united-states/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] The remaining 35 electoral votes were split among 10 candidates, including John Jay, who finished third with nine electoral votes.
[src:united-states/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] Three states were ineligible to participate in the election: New York's legislature did not choose electors on time, and North Carolina and Rhode Island had not yet ratified the constitution.
[src:united-states/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] Washington was inaugurated in New York City on April 30, 1789, 57 days after the First Congress convened.
[src:united-states/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] Both factions supported Washington for president.
[src:united-states/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] Limited, primitive political campaigning occurred in states and localities where swaying public opinion might have mattered.
[src:united-states/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] For example, in Maryland, a state with a statewide popular vote, unofficial parties campaigned locally, advertising.
[src:united-states/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] No nomination process existed at the time of planning, and thus, the framers of the Constitution presumed that Washington would be elected unopposed.
[src:united-states/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] Another uncertainty was the choice for the vice presidency, which contained no definite job description beyond being the president's designated successor and presiding over the Senate.
[src:united-states/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] The Constitution stipulated that the position would be awarded to the runner-up in the presidential election.
[src:united-states/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] Because Washington was from Virginia, then the largest state, many assumed that electors would choose a vice president from a northern state.
[src:united-states/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] Minister to France Thomas Jefferson wrote that he considered John Adams and John Hancock, both from Massachusetts, to be the top contenders.
[src:united-states/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] Jefferson suggested John Jay, John Rutledge, and Virginian James Madison as other possible candidates.
[src:united-states/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] Adams received 34 electoral votes, one short of a majority – because the Constitution did not require an outright majority in the Electoral College prior to ratification of the Twelfth Amendment to elect a runner-up as vice president, Adams was elected to that post.
[src:united-states/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] However, the states differed in their interpretations of this procedure and of the relevant portions of the new Constitution.
[src:united-states/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] New Hampshire and Massachusetts held a popular vote for their presidential electors alongside the elections for their representatives in the new Congress, on December 15 and December 18, respectively.
[src:united-states/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] In these two states, the legislatures ultimately chose the electors based on the voting results on the appointed day, January 7.
[src:united-states/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] In Delaware, Maryland, Pennsylvania, and Virginia, the electors were chosen directly by the popular vote on January 7.
[src:united-states/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] In Connecticut, Georgia, and South Carolina, the electors were appointed by the legislature alone on January 7, while in New Jersey the governor and council selected them on that day.
[src:united-states/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] The legislature in New York was unable to agree on a method for choosing the electors before January 7, and so the state could not appoint any electors.
[src:united-states/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] Voter turnout comprised a low single-digit percentage of the adult population.
[src:united-states/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] Though all states allowed some rudimentary form of popular vote, only six ratifying states allowed any form of popular vote specifically for presidential electors.
[src:united-states/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] In most states only white men, and in many only those who owned property, could vote.
[src:united-states/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] Free black men could vote in four Northern states, and women could vote in New Jersey until 1804.
[src:united-states/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] In some states, there was a nominal religious test for voting.
[src:united-states/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] For example, in Massachusetts and Connecticut, the Congregational Church was established, supported by taxes.
[src:united-states/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] Voting was hampered by poor communications and infrastructure and the labor demands imposed by farming.
[src:united-states/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] Two months passed after the election before the votes were counted and Washington was notified that he had been elected president.
[src:united-states/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] Washington spent eight days traveling from Virginia to New York for the inauguration.
[src:united-states/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] Congress took twenty-eight days to assemble.
[src:united-states/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] As the electors were selected, politics intruded, and the process was not free of rumors and intrigue.
[src:united-states/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] For example, Hamilton aimed to ensure that Adams did not inadvertently tie Washington in the electoral vote.
[src:united-states/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] Also, Federalists spread rumors that Anti-Federalists plotted to elect Richard Henry Lee or Patrick Henry president, with George Clinton as vice president.
[src:united-states/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] However, Clinton received only three electoral votes.
[src:united-states/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] Several respected sources, including the Biographical Directory of the United States Congress and the Political Graveyard, show this individual to be James Armstrong of Pennsylvania.
[src:united-states/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] However, primary sources, such as the Senate Journal, list only Armstrong's name, not his state.
[src:united-states/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] Skeptics observe that Armstrong received his single vote from a Georgia elector.
[src:united-states/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] Early presidential elections used a form of plurality block voting that preceded the widespread adoption of the general ticket.
[src:united-states/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] Under this system, voters elected each member of the Electoral College individually; electors nominated by the same political party often received differing numbers of votes as a consequence of voter rolloff, split-ticket voting, or electoral fusion.
[src:united-states/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] In most cases, this table calculates the popular vote of each state based on the votes for the leading Federalist and Anti-Federalist electors in each constituent county or township.
[src:united-states/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] In states where the electors were chosen from single-member districts, all votes for Federalist and Anti-Federalist electors are counted.
[src:united-states/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] Most townships in New Hampshire are missing data for this election; the figure shown is the result for the leading Federalist elector statewide.
[src:united-states/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] Because published compilations of the election results are missing labels for many electors, the estimate presented here is incomplete.
[src:united-states/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] As per the terms of the unamended constitution, each elector was permitted two votes for president, with a majority of "the whole number of electors appointed" necessary to elect a president.
[src:united-states/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] Of the 69 participating electors, each cast one vote for Washington, who was elected president.
[src:united-states/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] Of the remaining candidates, only Adams, Jay, and Hancock received votes from more than one state; with 34 votes, Adams finished second behind only Washington, and by virtue of which fact was elected vice president.
[src:united-states/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] Control of the bicameral New York State Legislature was divided following ratification of the federal constitution, and lawmakers could not reach an agreement to appoint electors for the forthcoming presidential contest.
[src:united-states/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] The fight to ratify the United States Constitution was still fresh in the memories of the legislators, and the Anti-Federalists were resentful for having been forced by events to accept the constitution without amendments.
[src:united-states/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] Bills to govern the selection of electors were proposed in each house and rejected by the other, leading to an impasse.
[src:united-states/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] The deadlock still stood on January 7, 1789, the last day for electors to be chosen by the states, and New York thus failed to appoint the eight electors allocated to it by the constitution.
[src:united-states/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] The Constitution, in Article II, Section 1, provided that the state legislatures should decide the manner in which their Electors were chosen.
[src:united-states/1876-united-states-presidential-election] Presidential elections were held in the United States on November 7, 1876.
[src:united-states/1876-united-states-presidential-election] The Republican ticket of Governor Rutherford B.
[src:united-states/1876-united-states-presidential-election] Hayes of Ohio and House Representative William A.
[src:united-states/1876-united-states-presidential-election] Wheeler of New York very narrowly defeated the Democratic ticket of Governor Samuel J.
[src:united-states/1876-united-states-presidential-election] Tilden of New York and Governor Thomas A.
[src:united-states/1876-united-states-presidential-election] Grant's decision to retire after his second term, U.S.
[src:united-states/1876-united-states-presidential-election] Blaine emerged as frontrunner for the Republican nomination; however, Blaine was unable to win a majority at the 1876 Republican National Convention, which settled on Hayes as a compromise candidate.
[src:united-states/1876-united-states-presidential-election] The 1876 Democratic National Convention nominated Tilden on the second ballot.
[src:united-states/1876-united-states-presidential-election] The election was among the most contentious in American history, and was widely speculated to have been resolved by the Compromise of 1877, in which Hayes supposedly agreed to end Reconstruction in exchange for the presidency.
[src:united-states/1876-united-states-presidential-election] In the first count, Tilden had 184 electoral votes (one vote short of a majority) to Hayes's 165, with the 20 votes from Florida, Louisiana, South Carolina, and Oregon disputed.
[src:united-states/1876-united-states-presidential-election] To address this constitutional crisis, Congress established the Electoral Commission, which awarded all twenty votes and thus the presidency to Hayes in a strict party-line vote.
[src:united-states/1876-united-states-presidential-election] Some Democratic representatives filibustered the commission's decision, hoping to prevent Hayes's inauguration; their filibuster was ultimately ended by party leader Samuel J.
[src:united-states/1876-united-states-presidential-election] On March 2, 1877, the House and Senate confirmed Hayes as president.
[src:united-states/1876-united-states-presidential-election] This was the last election taken under Reconstruction, in which some Southern states voted for a Republican candidate.
[src:united-states/1876-united-states-presidential-election] Following the election, Southern states were able to fully implement Jim Crow laws, disenfranchising black Americans, and beginning a period of Democratic domination known as the Solid South.
[src:united-states/1876-united-states-presidential-election] No Republican presidential nominee would win a former Confederate state until Warren G.
[src:united-states/1876-united-states-presidential-election] Harding in the 1920 United States presidential election.
[src:united-states/1876-united-states-presidential-election] It was the fifth of six consecutive presidential election victories for the Republican Party and the second of five U.S. presidential elections in which the winner did not win a plurality of the national popular vote, after the 1824 election.
[src:united-states/1876-united-states-presidential-election] Although Tilden defeated Hayes in the official popular vote tally, the election involved substantial electoral fraud, voter intimidation by paramilitary groups such as the Red Shirts, and disenfranchisement of black Republicans.
[src:united-states/1876-united-states-presidential-election] The election had the highest voter turnout of the eligible voting-age population in American history, at 82.6%.
[src:united-states/1876-united-states-presidential-election] Tilden's share of the popular vote, 50.9%, is the largest received by a candidate who was not elected to the presidency, and he was the first losing candidate in a U.S. presidential election who won a majority of the popular vote.
[src:united-states/1876-united-states-presidential-election] Tilden was also the last person to win an outright majority of the popular vote until William McKinley in 1896.
[src:united-states/1876-united-states-presidential-election] As of 2024, this remains the only presidential election in which both candidates were sitting governors, and was the last presidential election during which the presidential electors of a state (Colorado) were appointed at the discretion of the state legislature rather than by popular vote.
[src:united-states/1876-united-states-presidential-election] It was widely assumed during the year 1875 that incumbent President Ulysses S.
[src:united-states/1876-united-states-presidential-election] Grant would run for a third term as president despite the poor economic conditions, the numerous political scandals that had developed since he assumed office in 1869, and despite a longstanding tradition set by George Washington not to stay in office for more than two terms.
[src:united-states/1876-united-states-presidential-election] Grant's inner circle advised him to go for a third term and he almost did so, but on December 15, 1875, the House, by a sweeping 233–18 vote, passed a resolution declaring that the two-term tradition was to prevent a dictatorship.
[src:united-states/1876-united-states-presidential-election] Later that year, Grant ruled himself out of running in 1876.
[src:united-states/1876-united-states-presidential-election] He instead tried to persuade Secretary of State Hamilton Fish to run for the presidency, but the 67-year-old Fish declined since he believed himself too old for that role.
[src:united-states/1876-united-states-presidential-election] Grant nonetheless sent a letter to the convention imploring them to nominate Fish, but the letter was misplaced and never read to the convention.
[src:united-states/1876-united-states-presidential-election] Fish later confirmed that he would have declined the presidential nomination even if it had been offered to him.
[src:united-states/1876-united-states-presidential-election] When the Sixth Republican National Convention assembled in Cincinnati, Ohio, on June 14, 1876, James G.
[src:united-states/1876-united-states-presidential-election] Blaine appeared to be the presidential nominee.
[src:united-states/1876-united-states-presidential-election] On the first ballot, Blaine was just 100 votes short of a majority.
[src:united-states/1876-united-states-presidential-election] His vote began to slide after the second ballot, however, as many Republicans feared that Blaine could not win the general election.
[src:united-states/1876-united-states-presidential-election] Anti-Blaine delegates could not agree on a candidate until his total rose to 41% on the sixth ballot.
[src:united-states/1876-united-states-presidential-election] Leaders of the reform Republicans met privately and considered alternatives.
[src:united-states/1876-united-states-presidential-election] They chose the reforming Ohio Governor Rutherford B.
[src:united-states/1876-united-states-presidential-election] Hayes, who had been gradually building support during the convention until he finished second on the sixth ballot.
[src:united-states/1876-united-states-presidential-election] On the seventh ballot, Hayes was nominated for president with 384 votes, compared to 351 for Blaine and 21 for Benjamin Bristow.
[src:united-states/1876-united-states-presidential-election] Wheeler was nominated for vice president by a much larger margin (366–89) over his chief rival, Frederick Theodore Frelinghuysen, who later served as a member of the Electoral Commission, which awarded the election to Hayes.
[src:united-states/1876-united-states-presidential-election] The Democratic Party's failure to nominate its own ticket in the previous presidential election, in which they had instead endorsed the Liberal Republican candidacy of Horace Greeley, had resulted in much debate about the party's viability.
[src:united-states/1876-united-states-presidential-election] The 12th Democratic National Convention assembled in St.
[src:united-states/1876-united-states-presidential-election] Louis, Missouri, in June 1876, which was the first political convention ever held by one of the major American parties west of the Mississippi River.
[src:united-states/1876-united-states-presidential-election] There were 5000 people jammed inside the auditorium in St.
[src:united-states/1876-united-states-presidential-election] Louis amid hopes for the Democratic Party's first presidential victory in 20 years.
[src:united-states/1876-united-states-presidential-election] The platform called for immediate and sweeping reforms in response to the scandals that had plagued the Grant administration.
[src:united-states/1876-united-states-presidential-election] Tilden won more than 400 votes on the first ballot and the presidential nomination by a landslide on the second.
[src:united-states/1876-united-states-presidential-election] Hendricks, Winfield Scott Hancock, William Allen, Thomas F.
[src:united-states/1876-united-states-presidential-election] Bayard, and Joel Parker for the presidential nomination.
[src:united-states/1876-united-states-presidential-election] Tilden overcame strong opposition from "Honest John" Kelly, the leader of New York's Tammany Hall, to obtain the presidential nomination.
[src:united-states/1876-united-states-presidential-election] Thomas Hendricks was nominated for vice president since he was the only person to put forward for that position.
[src:united-states/1876-united-states-presidential-election] The Democratic platform pledged to replace the corruption of the Grant administration with honest, efficient government and to end "the rapacity of carpetbag tyrannies" in the South.
[src:united-states/1876-united-states-presidential-election] It also called for treaty protection for naturalized United States citizens visiting their homelands, restrictions on Asian immigration, tariff reform, and opposition to land grants for railroads.
[src:united-states/1876-united-states-presidential-election] It has been claimed that the voting Democrats received Tilden's presidential nomination with more enthusiasm than any leader since Andrew Jackson.
[src:united-states/1876-united-states-presidential-election] Source: *Official proceedings of the National Democratic convention, held in St.
[src:united-states/1876-united-states-presidential-election] The Greenback Party had been organized by agricultural interests in Indianapolis, Indiana, in 1874 to urge the federal government to inflate the economy through the mass issuance of paper money called greenbacks.
[src:united-states/1876-united-states-presidential-election] Its first national nominating convention was held in Indianapolis during the month of May 1876.
[src:united-states/1876-united-states-presidential-election] Peter Cooper was nominated for president with 352 votes to 119 for three other candidates.
[src:united-states/1876-united-states-presidential-election] The convention nominated Anti-Monopolist Senator Newton Booth of California for vice president.
[src:united-states/1876-united-states-presidential-election] After Booth declined to run, the national committee chose Samuel Fenton Cary as his replacement on the ticket.
[src:united-states/1876-united-states-presidential-election] The Prohibition Party, in its second national convention in Cleveland, nominated Green Clay Smith as its presidential candidate and Gideon T.
[src:united-states/1876-united-states-presidential-election] Stewart as its vice presidential candidate.
[src:united-states/1876-united-states-presidential-election] This small political party used several different names, often with different names in different states.
[src:united-states/1876-united-states-presidential-election] It was a continuation of the Anti-Masonic Party that met in 1872 and nominated Charles Francis Adams Sr., for president.
[src:united-states/1876-united-states-presidential-election] When Adams declined to run, the party did not contest the 1872 election.
[src:united-states/1876-united-states-presidential-election] The convention was held from June 8 to 10, 1875 in Liberty Hall, Pittsburgh, Pennsylvania.
[src:united-states/1876-united-states-presidential-election] Roberts of New York served as chairman, and Jonathan Blanchard was the keynote speaker.
[src:united-states/1876-united-states-presidential-election] The platform supported the Reconstruction Amendments to the Constitution, international arbitration, the reading of the scriptures in public schools, specie payments, justice for Native Americans, abolition of the Electoral College, and prohibition of the sale of alcoholic beverages.
[src:united-states/1876-united-states-presidential-election] It declared the first day of the week to be a day of rest for the United States.
[src:united-states/1876-united-states-presidential-election] The platform opposed secret societies and monopolies.
[src:united-states/1876-united-states-presidential-election] The convention considered three potential presidential candidates: Charles F.
[src:united-states/1876-united-states-presidential-election] When Blanchard declined to run, Walker was unanimously nominated for president.
[src:united-states/1876-united-states-presidential-election] The convention then nominated Donald Kirkpatrick of New York unanimously for vice president.
[src:united-states/1876-united-states-presidential-election] Tilden, who had prosecuted machine politicians in New York and sent the political boss William M.
[src:united-states/1876-united-states-presidential-election] Tweed to jail, ran as a reform candidate against the background of the corruption of the Grant administration.
[src:united-states/1876-united-states-presidential-election] Both parties backed civil service reform.
[src:united-states/1876-united-states-presidential-election] Both sides mounted mudslinging campaigns, with Democratic attacks on Republican corruption being countered by Republicans raising the Civil War issue, a tactic that was ridiculed by Democrats, who called it "waving the bloody shirt".
[src:united-states/1876-united-states-presidential-election] Hayes was a virtual unknown outside his home state of Ohio, where he had served two terms as a U.S. representative and then two terms as governor.
[src:united-states/1876-united-states-presidential-election] Henry Adams called Hayes "a third-rate nonentity whose only recommendations are that he is obnoxious to no one".
[src:united-states/1876-united-states-presidential-election] Hayes had served in the Civil War with distinction as colonel of the 23rd Ohio Regiment and was wounded several times, which made him marketable to veterans.
[src:united-states/1876-united-states-presidential-election] He had later been brevetted as a major-general.
[src:united-states/1876-united-states-presidential-election] His most important asset was his help to the Republican ticket in carrying Ohio, a crucial swing state.
[src:united-states/1876-united-states-presidential-election] On the other side, the newspaperman John D.
[src:united-states/1876-united-states-presidential-election] Defrees described Tilden as "a very nice, prim, little, withered-up, fidgety old bachelor, about one-hundred and twenty-pounds avoirdupois, who never had a genuine impulse for many nor any affection for woman".
[src:united-states/1876-united-states-presidential-election] The Democratic strategy for victory in the South relied on paramilitary groups such as the Red Shirts and the White League.
[src:united-states/1876-united-states-presidential-election] These groups saw themselves as the military wing of the Democrats.
[src:united-states/1876-united-states-presidential-election] Using the strategy of the Mississippi Plan, they actively suppressed both black and white Republican voting.
[src:united-states/1876-united-states-presidential-election] They violently disrupted meetings and rallies, attacked party organizers, and threatened potential voters with retaliation for voting Republican.
[src:united-states/1876-united-states-presidential-election] Because it was considered improper for a candidate to pursue the presidency actively, neither Tilden nor Hayes appeared publicly during the campaign.
[src:united-states/1876-united-states-presidential-election] Speaking and leading rallies were left to their surrogates.
[src:united-states/1876-united-states-presidential-election] Colorado was admitted to the Union as the 38th state on August 1, 1876; this was the first presidential election in which the state sent electors.
[src:united-states/1876-united-states-presidential-election] There was insufficient time or money to organize a presidential election in the new state.
[src:united-states/1876-united-states-presidential-election] Therefore, Colorado's state legislature selected the state's three members of the Electoral College.
[src:united-states/1876-united-states-presidential-election] The Republican Party held a slim majority in the state legislature following a closely contested election on October 3, 1876.
[src:united-states/1876-united-states-presidential-election] Many of the seats in that election had been decided by only a few hundred votes.
[src:united-states/1876-united-states-presidential-election] On November 7, 1876, in a 50 to 24 vote, the state legislature chose Otto Mears, William Hadley, and Herman Beckurts to serve as the state's electors for president.
[src:united-states/1876-united-states-presidential-election] All three of the state's electors cast their votes for Hayes.
[src:united-states/1876-united-states-presidential-election] This was the last election in which any state chose electors through its state legislature, rather than by popular vote.
[src:united-states/1876-united-states-presidential-election] Florida (with four electoral votes) and Louisiana (with eight) reported returns that favored Tilden, while Hayes led in South Carolina (with seven).
[src:united-states/1876-united-states-presidential-election] However, the elections in each state were marked by electoral fraud and threats of violence against Republican voters.
[src:united-states/1876-united-states-presidential-election] The most extreme case was in South Carolina, where an impossible 101 percent of all eligible voters in the state had their votes counted, and an estimated 150 Black Republicans were murdered.
[src:united-states/1876-united-states-presidential-election] One of the points of contention revolved around the design of ballots.
[src:united-states/1876-united-states-presidential-election] At the time, parties would print ballots or "tickets" to enable voters to support them in the open ballots.
[src:united-states/1876-united-states-presidential-election] To aid illiterate voters, the parties would print symbols on the tickets, and in this election, many Democratic ballots were printed with the Republican symbol of Abraham Lincoln on them.
[src:united-states/1876-united-states-presidential-election] The Republican-dominated state electoral commissions subsequently rejected enough Democratic votes to award their electoral votes to Hayes.
[src:united-states/1876-united-states-presidential-election] In two Southern states, the governor recognized by the United States had signed the Republican certificates; the Democratic certificates from Florida were signed by the state attorney-general and the newly elected Democratic governor.
[src:united-states/1876-united-states-presidential-election] Those from Louisiana were signed by the Democratic gubernatorial candidate and those from South Carolina by no state official.
[src:united-states/1876-united-states-presidential-election] The Tilden electors in South Carolina claimed that they had been chosen by the popular vote although they were rejected by the state election board.
[src:united-states/1876-united-states-presidential-election] Meanwhile, in Oregon, the vote of a single elector was disputed.
[src:united-states/1876-united-states-presidential-election] The two Republican electors dismissed Grover's action and reported three votes for Hayes.
[src:united-states/1876-united-states-presidential-election] Cronin, reported one vote for Tilden and two votes for Hayes.
[src:united-states/1876-united-states-presidential-election] The two Republican electors presented a certificate signed by the secretary of state of Oregon, and Cronin and the two electors whom he appointed (Cronin voted for Tilden while his associates voted for Hayes) presented a certificate signed by the governor and attested by the secretary of state.
[src:united-states/1876-united-states-presidential-election] Ultimately, all three of Oregon's votes were awarded to Hayes, who had a majority of one in the Electoral College.
[src:united-states/1876-united-states-presidential-election] The Democrats claimed fraud, and suppressed excitement pervaded the country.
[src:united-states/1876-united-states-presidential-election] Threats were even muttered that Hayes would never be inaugurated.
[src:united-states/1876-united-states-presidential-election] In Columbus, Ohio, a shot was fired at Hayes's residence as he sat down to dinner.
[src:united-states/1876-united-states-presidential-election] After supporters marched to his home to call for the President, Hayes urged the crowd that "it is impossible, at so early a time, to obtain the result".
[src:united-states/1876-united-states-presidential-election] Grant quietly strengthened the military force in and around Washington.
[src:united-states/1876-united-states-presidential-election] The Democrats objected to that construction, since the President Pro Tempore of the Senate, the Republican Thomas W.
[src:united-states/1876-united-states-presidential-election] Ferry, could then count the votes of the disputed states for Hayes.
[src:united-states/1876-united-states-presidential-election] The Democrats insisted that Congress should continue the practice followed since 1865: no vote objected to should be counted except by the concurrence of both houses.
[src:united-states/1876-united-states-presidential-election] Since the House had a solid Democratic majority, rejecting the vote of one state, therefore, would elect Tilden.
[src:united-states/1876-united-states-presidential-election] Facing an unprecedented constitutional crisis, the Congress passed a law on January 29, 1877, to form a 15-member Electoral Commission, which would settle the result.
[src:united-states/1876-united-states-presidential-election] Five members were selected from each house of Congress, and they were joined by five members of the United States Supreme Court, with William M.
[src:united-states/1876-united-states-presidential-election] Evarts serving as counsel for the Republican Party.
[src:united-states/1876-united-states-presidential-election] The majority party in each house named three members and the minority party two members.
[src:united-states/1876-united-states-presidential-election] As the Republicans controlled the Senate and the Democrats controlled the House of Representatives, that yielded five Democratic and five Republican members of the commission.
[src:united-states/1876-united-states-presidential-election] Of the Supreme Court justices, two Republicans and two Democrats were chosen, with the fifth to be selected by those four.
[src:united-states/1876-united-states-presidential-election] The justices first selected the independent Justice David Davis.
[src:united-states/1876-united-states-presidential-election] However, they had miscalculated, as Davis promptly excused himself from the commission and resigned as a Justice to take his Senate seat.
[src:united-states/1876-united-states-presidential-election] As all of the remaining available Justices were Republicans, Republican Justice Joseph P.
[src:united-states/1876-united-states-presidential-election] Bradley, who was considered the most impartial remaining member of the court was selected.
[src:united-states/1876-united-states-presidential-election] It was drawing perilously near to Inauguration Day, and thus the commission met on January 31.
[src:united-states/1876-united-states-presidential-election] Each of the disputed state election cases (Florida, Louisiana, Oregon, and South Carolina) was respectively submitted to the commission by Congress.
[src:united-states/1876-united-states-presidential-election] Eminent counsel appeared for each side, and there were double sets of returns from every one of the states named.
[src:united-states/1876-united-states-presidential-election] The commission first decided not to question any returns that were *prima facie* lawful.
[src:united-states/1876-united-states-presidential-election] Bradley then joined the other seven Republican committee members in a series of 8–7 votes that gave all 20 disputed electoral votes to Hayes, which gave Hayes a 185–184 electoral vote victory.
[src:united-states/1876-united-states-presidential-election] Hayes privately took the oath of office the next day and was publicly sworn into office on March 5, 1877, and Hayes was inaugurated without disturbance.
[src:united-states/1876-united-states-presidential-election] The Compromise of 1877 might be a reason for the Democrats accepting the Electoral Commission.
[src:united-states/1876-united-states-presidential-election] During intense closed-door meetings, Democratic leaders agreed reluctantly to accept Hayes as president in return for the withdrawal of federal troops from the last two Southern states that were still occupied: South Carolina and Louisiana.
[src:united-states/1876-united-states-presidential-election] Republican leaders in return agreed on a number of handouts and entitlements, including federal subsidies for a transcontinental railroad line through the South.
[src:united-states/1876-united-states-presidential-election] Although some of the promises were not kept, particularly the railroad proposal, that was enough for the time being to avert a dangerous standoff.
[src:united-states/1876-united-states-presidential-election] The returns accepted by the Commission put Hayes's margin of victory in South Carolina at 889 votes, the second-closest popular vote margin in a decisive state in U.S. history, after the election of 2000, which was decided by 537 votes in Florida.
[src:united-states/1876-united-states-presidential-election] In 2000, the margin of victory in the Electoral College for George W.
[src:united-states/1876-united-states-presidential-election] Bush was five votes, as opposed to Hayes' one vote.
[src:united-states/1876-united-states-presidential-election] Congress would eventually enact the Electoral Count Act in 1887 to provide more detailed rules for the counting of electoral votes, especially in cases of multiple slates of electors being received from a single state.
[src:united-states/1876-united-states-presidential-election] 37.1% of the voting age population and 82.6% of eligible voters participated in the election.
[src:united-states/1876-united-states-presidential-election] According to the commission's rulings, of the 2,249 counties and independent cities making returns, Tilden won in 1,301 (57.9%), and Hayes carried only 947 (42.1%).
[src:united-states/1876-united-states-presidential-election] One county (<0.1%) in Nevada split evenly between Tilden and Hayes.
[src:united-states/1876-united-states-presidential-election] The Greenback ticket did not have a major impact on the election's outcome by attracting slightly under one percent of the popular vote; nonetheless, Cooper had the strongest performance of any third-party presidential candidate since John Bell in 1860.
[src:united-states/1876-united-states-presidential-election] The Greenbacks' best showings were in Kansas, where Cooper earned just over six percent of the vote, and in Indiana, where he earned 17,207 votes, which far exceeded Tilden's margin of victory of roughly 5,500 votes over Hayes in that state.
[src:united-states/1876-united-states-presidential-election] The election of 1876 was the last one held before the end of the Reconstruction era, which sought to protect the rights of African Americans in the South, who usually voted for Republican presidential candidates.
[src:united-states/1876-united-states-presidential-election] No antebellum slave state would be carried by a Republican again until the 1896 realignment, which saw William McKinley carry Delaware, Maryland, West Virginia, and Kentucky.
[src:united-states/1876-united-states-presidential-election] This is the closest electoral college result in American history, and the second-closest victory in the tipping point state with South Carolina being decided by 889 votes (only the 2000 election in Florida was closer).
[src:united-states/1876-united-states-presidential-election] No Republican presidential candidate until Warren G.
[src:united-states/1876-united-states-presidential-election] Harding in 1920 would carry any states that seceded and joined the Confederacy.
[src:united-states/1876-united-states-presidential-election] That year, he carried Tennessee, which had never experienced a long period of occupation by federal troops and had been completely "reconstructed" well before the first presidential election of the Reconstruction period (1868).
[src:united-states/1876-united-states-presidential-election] None of the Southern states that experienced long periods of occupation by federal troops was carried by a Republican again until Herbert Hoover in 1928, when he won Florida, North Carolina, Texas and Virginia.
[src:united-states/1876-united-states-presidential-election] 1876 proved to be the last election until 1956 in which the Republican nominee carried Louisiana, as well as the last in which the Republican won South Carolina until 1964.
[src:united-states/1876-united-states-presidential-election] Both states would not defect from the Democratic ticket again until 1948, when they backed the "Dixiecrat" candidate Strom Thurmond.
[src:united-states/1876-united-states-presidential-election] 18.33% of Hayes' votes came from the eleven states of the former Confederacy, with him taking 40.40% of the vote in that region.
[src:united-states/1876-united-states-presidential-election] As of 2024, Hayes is the only Republican president ever to be elected who failed to carry Indiana, and was the first to win without Connecticut.
[src:united-states/1876-united-states-presidential-election] This was also the last presidential election until 2016 that Florida voted Republican while Virginia voted Democratic.
[src:united-states/1876-united-states-presidential-election] Source: Data from Walter Dean Burnham, *Presidential ballots, 1836–1892* (Johns Hopkins University Press, 1955) pp 247–57.
[src:united-states/1904-summer-olympics] The **1904 Summer Olympics** (officially the **Games of the III Olympiad** and also known as **St.
[src:united-states/1904-summer-olympics] Louis 1904**) were an international multi-sport event held in St.
[src:united-states/1904-summer-olympics] Louis, Missouri, United States, from 1 July to 23 November 1904.
[src:united-states/1904-summer-olympics] Many events were conducted at what is now known as Francis Field on the campus of Washington University in St.
[src:united-states/1904-summer-olympics] This was the first time that the Olympic Games were held outside Europe.
[src:united-states/1904-summer-olympics] Tensions caused by the Russo–Japanese War and difficulties in traveling to St.
[src:united-states/1904-summer-olympics] Louis resulted in very few top-class athletes from outside the United States and Canada taking part in the 1904 Games.
[src:united-states/1904-summer-olympics] Only 69–74 of the 651 athletes who competed came from outside North America, and only between 12 and 15 nations were represented in all.
[src:united-states/1904-summer-olympics] Some events subsequently combined the U.S. national championship with the Olympic championship.
[src:united-states/1904-summer-olympics] The current three-medal format of gold, silver and bronze for first, second and third place was introduced at the 1904 Olympics.
[src:united-states/1904-summer-olympics] After the first two editions of the Olympic Games were awarded to Athens and Paris, the IOC's first open bidding process was held for the 1904 Olympics at the 4th IOC Session in Paris in May 1901.
[src:united-states/1904-summer-olympics] Chicago civic leaders, including University of Chicago president William Rainey Harper, formed the International Olympian Games Association in February 1901 to plan for hosting the Olympics.
[src:united-states/1904-summer-olympics] Shortly before the session began, another American bid was submitted from St.
[src:united-states/1904-summer-olympics] Louis, which was then preparing to host the Louisiana Purchase Exposition, a World's Fair in 1903.
[src:united-states/1904-summer-olympics] At the session, representatives of Chicago offered to put $100,000 (equivalent to $3,870,000 in 2025) toward the games.
[src:united-states/1904-summer-olympics] Unable to compete with this, all other countries withdrew their bids before the IOC voted; cities which had previously expressed interest in the 1904 games included Berlin, Copenhagen, and Stockholm.
[src:united-states/1904-summer-olympics] The IOC delegates then voted between the choices of Chicago and St.
[src:united-states/1904-summer-olympics] Louis, with Chicago winning unanimously on May 21.
[src:united-states/1904-summer-olympics] Louis was forced to postpone its World's Fair from 1903 to 1904, it began planning athletic events that would compete directly with the Olympics in Chicago.
[src:united-states/1904-summer-olympics] Louis and planned to hold its national championships at the World's Fair.
[src:united-states/1904-summer-olympics] In the meantime, Chicago's plans for a new stadium on the shore of Lake Michigan seating 75,000 met considerable opposition from local leaders, including Aaron Montgomery Ward, putting the centerpiece of Chicago's Olympic bid into question.
[src:united-states/1904-summer-olympics] On December 23, 1902, fearing that the dispute would permanently damage the Olympic movement, the IOC asked its members to approve, by a postal vote, the transfer of the Olympic Games to St.
[src:united-states/1904-summer-olympics] When the votes were tallied, IOC founder Pierre de Coubertin telegraphed the Chicago committee on February 10, 1903, to inform them that the Games had been moved.
[src:united-states/1904-summer-olympics] Boxing, dumbbells, catch wrestling (which later became freestyle wrestling), and the decathlon made their debuts.
[src:united-states/1904-summer-olympics] The swimming events were held in a temporary pond near Skinker and Wydown Boulevards, where "lifesaving demonstrations" of unsinkable lifeboats for ocean liners took place.
[src:united-states/1904-summer-olympics] Chicago runner James Lightbody won the steeplechase and the 800 m and then set a natural world record in the 1500 m.
[src:united-states/1904-summer-olympics] Harry Hillman won both the 200 m and 400 m hurdles and also the flat 400 m.
[src:united-states/1904-summer-olympics] Sprinter Archie Hahn was champion in the 60 m, 100 m and 200 m.
[src:united-states/1904-summer-olympics] In this last race, he set an Olympic record in 21.6, a natural record that stood for 28 years.
[src:united-states/1904-summer-olympics] In the discus, after American Martin Sheridan had thrown exactly the same distance as his compatriot, Ralph Rose (39.28 m), the judges gave them both an extra throw to decide the winner.
[src:united-states/1904-summer-olympics] Sheridan won the decider and claimed the gold medal.
[src:united-states/1904-summer-olympics] Ray Ewry again won all three standing jumps.
[src:united-states/1904-summer-olympics] The team representing Great Britain was awarded a total of two medals, both won by Irish athletes.
[src:united-states/1904-summer-olympics] The top non-U.S. athlete was Emil Rausch of Germany, who won three swimming events.
[src:united-states/1904-summer-olympics] Zoltán Halmay of Hungary and Charles Daniels of the United States each won two swimming gold medals.
[src:united-states/1904-summer-olympics] Galt Football Club from Canada won the gold medal in football.
[src:united-states/1904-summer-olympics] The organizers of the World's Fair held "Anthropology Days" on August 12 and 13.
[src:united-states/1904-summer-olympics] Since the 1889 Paris Exposition, human zoos, as a key feature of world's fairs, functioned as demonstrations of anthropological notions of race, progress, and civilization.
[src:united-states/1904-summer-olympics] These goals were followed also at the 1904 World's Fair.
[src:united-states/1904-summer-olympics] Fourteen hundred indigenous people from Southeast Asia, the Pacific Islands, East Asia, Africa, the Middle East, South America and North America were displayed in anthropological exhibits that showed them in their natural habitats.
[src:united-states/1904-summer-olympics] Another 1600 indigenous people displayed their culture in other areas of the Louisiana Purchase Exposition (LPE), including on the fairgrounds and at the Model School, where American Indian boarding schools students demonstrated their successful assimilation.
[src:united-states/1904-summer-olympics] The sporting event itself took place with the participation of about 100 paid indigenous men.
[src:united-states/1904-summer-olympics] Contests included "baseball throwing, shot put, running, broad jumping, weight lifting, pole climbing, and tugs-of-war before a crowd of approximately ten thousand".
[src:united-states/1904-summer-olympics] No women participated in Anthropology Days, though some, notably the Fort Shaw Indian School girls basketball team, did compete in other athletic events at the LPE.
[src:united-states/1904-summer-olympics] According to theorist Susan Brownell, world's fairs – with their inclusion of human zoos – and the Olympics were a logical fit at this time, as they "were both linked to an underlying cultural logic that gave them a natural affinity".
[src:united-states/1904-summer-olympics] Also, one of the original intentions of Anthropology Days was to create publicity for the official Olympic events.
[src:united-states/1904-summer-olympics] The 1904 Summer Olympic program featured 16 sports encompassing 95 events in 18 disciplines.
[src:united-states/1904-summer-olympics] Swimming, diving and water polo are considered three disciplines of the same sport, *aquatics*.
[src:united-states/1904-summer-olympics] In July 2021 the IOC accepted the recommendation of Olympic historian Bill Mallon regarding which sports and events should be considered as Olympic.
[src:united-states/1904-summer-olympics] The number of events in each discipline is noted in parentheses.
[src:united-states/1904-summer-olympics] Boxing made its Olympic debut at the St.
[src:united-states/1904-summer-olympics] The sport has since featured at every Summer Olympics, except for the 1912 Stockholm Games.
[src:united-states/1904-summer-olympics] While wrestling made a return, it was exclusively the newly debuted catch wrestling (which later became freestyle wrestling) as opposed to Greco-Roman style of the 1896 Summer Olympics.
[src:united-states/1904-summer-olympics] Five nations were represented, with each of the 42 competitors having resided in the United States.
[src:united-states/1904-summer-olympics] Later editions would have both styles of wrestling in their programs.
[src:united-states/1904-summer-olympics] Basketball, hurling, American football and Gaelic football were featured as unofficial sports.
[src:united-states/1904-summer-olympics] There was a demonstration bout of women's boxing.
[src:united-states/1904-summer-olympics] Baseball is also noted by the World Baseball Softball Confederation to have appeared at the Games, though it does not appear in the list compiled by Olympic historian Bill Mallon and any results are not known.
[src:united-states/1904-summer-olympics] Creve Coeur Lake is located further west.
[src:united-states/1904-summer-olympics] Five sports venues were used for the 1904 Summer Olympics.
[src:united-states/1904-summer-olympics] The venues included Glen Echo Country Club, the first golf course constructed west of the Mississippi River, which had opened in 1901.
[src:united-states/1904-summer-olympics] Three Olympic sports were hosted at Forest Park, the site of the Louisiana Purchase Exposition which was being held concurrently with the Olympics: the Life Saving Exhibition Lake at Forest Park was used for the diving, swimming, and water polo events.
[src:united-states/1904-summer-olympics] Creve Coeur Lake became the first park of St.
[src:united-states/1904-summer-olympics] The Lake has hosted rowing regattas since 1882 and still hosts them as of 2010.
[src:united-states/1904-summer-olympics] Francis Olympic Field and Gymnasium are still in use on the Washington University in St.
[src:united-states/1904-summer-olympics] An ornamental gate commemorating the 1904 Games was constructed outside the stadium immediately after the Exposition.
[src:united-states/1904-summer-olympics] A swimming pool was added to the gymnasium in 1985.
[src:united-states/1904-summer-olympics] Forest Park, constructed in 1876, is still in use as of 2021 and attracts over 12 million visitors annually.
[src:united-states/1904-summer-olympics] Glen Echo Country Club remains in use as a golf course today as of 2021.
[src:united-states/1904-summer-olympics] Athletes from thirteen nations competed in St.
[src:united-states/1904-summer-olympics] Numbers in parentheses indicate the number of known competitors for each nation.
[src:united-states/1904-summer-olympics] Louis in 1904, and European tensions caused by the Russo-Japanese War, only 69–74 athletes from outside North America participated in the Olympics.
[src:united-states/1904-summer-olympics] These are the nations that won medals at the 1904 Games.
[src:united-states/1904-summer-olympics] The nationalities of some medalists were disputed, as many American athletes were recent immigrants to the United States who had not yet been granted U.S. citizenship.
[src:united-states/1904-summer-olympics] These cases saw medals credited to the United States transferred to other countries or mixed teams.
[src:united-states/1904-summer-olympics] In addition, the IOC had counted one gold, one silver, and two bronze medals won by the American fencer Albertson Van Zo Post for Cuba instead of the United States.
[src:united-states/1904-summer-olympics] The IOC also had shown Charles Tatham as a Cuban medal-winner for individual fencing events (foil and épée) and American silver medalist in the team foil event, but he was an American.
[src:united-states/1904-summer-olympics] All are now credited to the United States.
[src:united-states/1916-danish-west-indies-status-referendum] An unofficial referendum on the sale of the islands to the United States was held in the Danish West Indies on 17 August 1916.
[src:united-states/1916-danish-west-indies-status-referendum] The proposal was approved by 99.83% of voters, with only seven people voting against.
[src:united-states/1916-danish-west-indies-status-referendum] It followed the Treaty of the Danish West Indies, which was signed on 4 August, and also approved by a referendum in Denmark in December 1916.
[src:united-states/1916-danish-west-indies-status-referendum] The islands were transferred to the United States in 1917.
[src:united-states/1916-danish-west-indies-status-referendum] No vote was held on Water Island, which had been sold by Denmark to the East Asiatic Company, a private shipping company, in 1905, and was no longer part of the colony.
[src:united-states/page] The explicitly double-barred (Dollar sign with two vertical lines) sign is called *cifrão* in the Portuguese language.
[src:united-states/page] The sign is also used in several compound currency symbols, such as the Brazilian real (R$) and the United States dollar (US$): in local use, the nationality prefix is usually omitted.
[src:united-states/page] In countries that have other currency symbols, the US dollar is often assumed and the "US" prefix omitted.
[src:united-states/page] The one- and two-stroke versions are often considered mere stylistic (typeface) variants, although in some places and epochs one of them may have been specifically assigned, by law or custom, to a specific currency.
[src:united-states/page] The Unicode computer encoding standard defines a single code for both.
[src:united-states/page] In most English-speaking countries that use that symbol, it is placed to the left of the amount specified, e.g.
[src:united-states/page] The symbol appears in business correspondence in the 1770s from the West Indies referring to the Spanish American peso, also known as "Spanish dollar" or "piece of eight" in British America.
[src:united-states/page] The Spanish coins provided the model for the currency that the United States adopted in 1792, and for the larger coins of the new Spanish American republics, such as the Mexican peso, Argentine peso, Peruvian real, and Bolivian sol coins.
[src:united-states/page] With the Coinage Act of 1792, the United States Congress created the U.S. dollar, defining it to have "the value of a Spanish milled dollar as the same is now current" but a variety of foreign coins were deemed to be legal tender until the Coinage Act of 1857 ended this status.
[src:united-states/page] The earliest U.S. dollar coins did not have any dollar symbol.
[src:united-states/page] The first occurrence in print is claimed to be from 1790s, by a Philadelphia printer Archibald Binny, creator of the Monticello typeface.
[src:united-states/page] The $1 United States Note issued by the United States in 1869 included a large symbol consisting of a 'U' with the right bar overlapping an 'S' like a single-bar dollar sign, as well as a very small double-stroke dollar sign in the legal warning against forgery *see picture*.
[src:united-states/page] It is still uncertain, however, how the dollar sign came to represent the Spanish American peso.
[src:united-states/page] The numerous currencies called "dollar" use the dollar sign to express money amounts.
[src:united-states/page] The sign is also generally used for the many currencies called "peso" (except the Philippine peso, which uses the symbol "₱").
[src:united-states/page] Within a country the dollar/peso sign may be used alone.
[src:united-states/page] In other cases, and to avoid ambiguity in international usage, it is usually combined with other glyphs, e.g.
[src:united-states/page] Particularly in professional contexts, the unambiguous ISO 4217 three letter code (AUD, MXN, USD, etc.) is preferred.
[src:united-states/page] The exception is French-speaking Canada, where the dollar symbol usually appears after the number, the same as the spoken order, e.g., "5 $" for "*cinq dollars*".
[src:united-states/page] In Portugal, Brazil, and other parts of the Portuguese Empire, the two-stroke variant of the sign named ***cifrão*** (Portuguese pronunciation: [siˈfɾɐ̃w] ⓘ; plural *cifrões*) has been used as the thousands separator in the national currency, the real (plural "réis", abbreviated "Rs.").
[src:united-states/page] For instance, 123(Dollar sign with two vertical lines)500 would be equivalent to 123500 réis.
[src:united-states/page] This usage is attested in 1775, but may be older by a century or more.
[src:united-states/page] The cifrão is always written with two vertical lines like (Dollar sign with two vertical lines), and is the official sign of the Cape Verdean escudo (ISO 4217: CVE).
[src:united-states/page] In 1911, Portugal redefined the national currency as the escudo, worth 1000 réis, and divided into 100 *centavos*; but the *cifrão* continued to be used as the decimal separator, so that 123(Dollar sign with two vertical lines)50 meant 123.50 escudos or 123 escudos and 50 centavos.
[src:united-states/page] This usage ended in 2002 when the country switched to the euro.
[src:united-states/page] Cape Verde, a republic and former Portuguese colony, similarly switched from the real to their local escudo and centavos in 1914, and retains the *cifrão* usage as decimals separator as of 2021.
[src:united-states/page] Brazil retained the real and the *cifrão* as thousands separator until 1942, when it switched to the Brazilian cruzeiro, with comma as the decimals separator.
[src:united-states/page] The dollar sign, officially with one stroke but often rendered with two, was retained as part of the currency symbol "Cr$", so one would write Cr$13,50 for 13 cruzeiros and 50 centavos.
[src:united-states/page] The *cifrão* was formerly used by the Portuguese escudo (ISO: PTE) before its replacement by the euro and by the Portuguese Timor escudo (ISO: TPE) before its replacement by the Indonesian rupiah and the US dollar.
[src:united-states/page] In Portuguese and Cape Verdean usage, the *cifrão* is placed as a decimal point between the escudo and *centavo* values.
[src:united-states/page] The name originates in the Arabic *ṣifr* (‏صِفْر‎), meaning 'zero'.
[src:united-states/page] Outside the Portuguese cultural sphere, the South Vietnamese đồng before 1975 used a method similar to the *cifrão* to separate values of đồng from its decimal subunit *xu*.
[src:united-states/page] For example, 7(Dollar sign with two vertical lines)50 meant 7 đồng and 50 xu.
[src:united-states/page] In some places and at some times, the one- and two-stroke variants have been used in the same contexts to distinguish between the U.S. dollar and other local currency, such as the former Portuguese escudo.
[src:united-states/page] However, such usage is not standardized, and the Unicode specification considers the two versions as graphic variants of the same symbol—a typeface design choice.
[src:united-states/page] Computer and typewriter keyboards usually have a single key for that sign, and many character encodings (including ASCII and Unicode) reserve a single numeric code for it.
[src:united-states/page] Indeed, dollar signs in the same digital document may be rendered with one or two strokes, if different computer fonts are used, but the underlying codepoint U+0024 (ASCII 3610) remains unchanged.
[src:united-states/page] When a specific variant is not mandated by law or custom, the choice is usually a matter of expediency or aesthetic preference.
[src:united-states/page] Both versions were used in the US in the 18th century.
[src:united-states/page] (An 1861 Civil War-era advertisement depicts the two-stroked symbol as a snake.) The two-stroke version seems to be generally less popular today, though used in some "old-style" fonts like Baskerville.
[src:united-states/page] Because of its use in early American computer applications such as business accounting, the dollar sign is almost universally present in computer character sets, and thus has been appropriated for many purposes unrelated to money in programming languages and command languages.
[src:united-states/page] The dollar sign "$" has ASCII and Unicode code point U+0024 (in Unicode's Latin-1 block inherited from ASCII).
[src:united-states/page] There are no separate encodings for one- and two-line variants.
[src:united-states/page] The choice is typeface-dependent; they are allographs.
[src:united-states/page] However, there are three other code points that originate from other East Asian standards: the Taiwanese small form variant, the CJK fullwidth form, and the Japanese emoji.
[src:united-states/page] The glyphs for these code points are typically larger or smaller than the primary code point, but the difference is mostly aesthetic or typographic, and the meanings of the symbols are the same.
[src:united-states/page] However, for usage as the special character in various computing applications (see following sections), U+0024 is typically the only code that is recognized.
[src:united-states/page] Support for the two-line variant varies.
[src:united-states/page] As of 2019, the Unicode standard considers the distinction between one- and two-bar dollar signs a stylistic distinction between fonts, and has no separate code point for the *cifrão*.
[src:united-states/page] The symbol is not in the October 2019 "pipeline", though it has been requested formally.
[src:united-states/page] In LaTeX, with the textcomp package installed, the *cifrão* ((Dollar sign with two vertical lines)) can be input using the command `\textdollaroldstyle`.
[src:united-states/page] However, because of font substitution and the lack of a dedicated code point, the author of an electronic document who uses one of these fonts intending to represent a *cifrão* cannot be sure that every reader will see a double-bar glyph rather than the single barred version.
[src:united-states/page] Because of the continued lack of support in Unicode, a single bar dollar sign is frequently employed in its place even for official purposes.
[src:united-states/page] Where there is any risk of misunderstanding, the ISO 4217 three-letter acronym is used.
[src:united-states/page] The character U+3326 ㌦ SQUARE DORU is a squared word version of ドル (*doru* "dollar", in Japanese).
[src:united-states/page] The character U+5F17 弗 CJK UNIFIED IDEOGRAPH-5F17 has been formerly repurposed as a symbol for dollars in Japan because of its visual similarity.
[src:united-states/page] The symbol is sometimes used derisively, in place of the letter S, to indicate greed or excess money such as in "Micro$oft", "Di$ney", "Chel$ea" and "GW$"; or supposed overt Americanization as in "$ky".
[src:united-states/page] The dollar sign is also used intentionally to stylize names such as A$AP Rocky, Ke$ha, and Ty Dolla $ign or words such as ¥€$.
[src:united-states/page] In 1872, Ambrose Bierce referred to California governor Leland Stanford as $tealand Landford.
[src:united-states/page] In Scrabble notation, a dollar sign is placed after a word to indicate that it is valid according to the North American word lists, but not according to the British word lists.
[src:united-states/page] A dollar symbol is used as unit of reactivity for a nuclear reactor, 0 $ being the threshold of slow criticality, meaning a steady reaction rate, while 1 $ is the threshold of prompt criticality, which means a nuclear excursion or explosion.
[src:united-states/page] In the 1993 version of the Turkmen Latin alphabet $ was used as a transliteration of the Cyrillic letter Ш, in 1999 was replaced by the letter Ş.
[src:united-states/united-states-p01] The **United States of America** (**USA**), also known as the **United States** (**U.S.**) or **America**, is a country primarily located in North America.
[src:united-states/united-states-p01] It is a federal republic consisting of 50 states and a federal capital district, Washington, D.C.
[src:united-states/united-states-p01] The 48 contiguous states border Canada to the north and Mexico to the south, with the semi-exclave of Alaska in the northwest and the archipelago of Hawaii in the Pacific Ocean.
[src:united-states/united-states-p01] The United States also asserts sovereignty over five major island territories and various uninhabited islands in Oceania and the Caribbean.
[src:united-states/united-states-p01] It is a megadiverse country, with the world's third-largest land area and third-largest population, exceeding 341 million.
[src:united-states/united-states-p01] Paleo-Indians first migrated from North Asia to North America at least 15,000 years ago, and formed various civilizations.
[src:united-states/united-states-p01] European discovery of the Americas began in 1492, and British colonization followed with the 1607 settlement of Virginia, the first of the Thirteen Colonies.
[src:united-states/united-states-p01] The American Enlightenment that spread throughout the colonies in the 18th century valued republicanism and liberalism.
[src:united-states/united-states-p01] Clashes with the British Crown over taxation without parliamentary representation and the denial of other English rights evolved into the American Revolution, which led to the July 2, 1776, Lee Resolution formally declaring independence from Great Britain.
[src:united-states/united-states-p01] This was followed two days later, on the Fourth of July, by the adoption and public release of the Declaration of Independence.
[src:united-states/united-states-p01] Victory in the 1775–1783 Revolutionary War brought international recognition of the country's sovereignty.
[src:united-states/united-states-p01] Rapid westward territorial expansion followed the purchase, settlement, and conquest of European and Indigenous-controlled territory.
[src:united-states/united-states-p01] As more states were admitted into the Union, a North–South division over slavery led 11 Southern states to declare secession and join as the Confederate States of America in order to preserve slavery there.
[src:united-states/united-states-p01] These states fought against the Union in the American Civil War of 1861–1865 but were defeated.
[src:united-states/united-states-p01] With the United States' victory and reunification, slavery was abolished nationally.
[src:united-states/united-states-p01] By 1900, the country had established itself as a great power, a status solidified after its involvement during World War I.
[src:united-states/united-states-p01] Following Japan's attack on Pearl Harbor in 1941, the U.S. entered World War II on the side of the Allies.
[src:united-states/united-states-p01] Its aftermath left the U.S. and the Soviet Union as rival superpowers, competing for ideological dominance and international influence during the Cold War.
[src:united-states/united-states-p01] The Soviet Union's collapse in 1991 left the U.S. as the world's sole superpower, although China has been widely cited since the 2020s as potentially achieving the same status.
[src:united-states/united-states-p01] The federal government is a representative democracy with a president and a constitution that creates a separation of powers among three branches: legislative, executive, and judicial.
[src:united-states/united-states-p01] The Congress is a bicameral national legislature composed of the House of Representatives (a lower house based on population) and the Senate (an upper house based on equal representation for each state).
[src:united-states/united-states-p01] Federalism grants substantial autonomy to the 50 states.
[src:united-states/united-states-p01] A developed country, the U.S. ranks high in economic competitiveness, innovation, and higher education.
[src:united-states/united-states-p01] Accounting for over a quarter of nominal global GDP, its economy has been the world's largest since about 1890.
[src:united-states/united-states-p01] It is the wealthiest country, with the highest disposable household income per capita among OECD members, though its wealth inequality is highly pronounced.
[src:united-states/united-states-p01] Shaped by centuries of immigration, the culture of the U.S. is diverse and globally influential.
[src:united-states/united-states-p01] Making up nearly a third of global military spending, the country is widely considered to have the most powerful armed forces in the world and was the first to develop and employ nuclear weapons.
[src:united-states/united-states-p01] A member of numerous international organizations including the United Nations Security Council, it plays a major role in global political, cultural, economic, and military affairs.
[src:united-states/united-states-p01] Documented use of the phrase "United States of America" dates back to January 2, 1776.
[src:united-states/united-states-p01] On that day, Stephen Moylan, a Continental Army aide to General George Washington, wrote a letter to Joseph Reed, Washington's aide-de-camp, seeking to go "with full and ample powers from the United States of America to Spain" to seek assistance in the Revolutionary War effort.
[src:united-states/united-states-p01] The first known public usage is an anonymous essay published in the Williamsburg newspaper *The Virginia Gazette* on April 6, 1776.
[src:united-states/united-states-p01] Sometime on or after June 11, 1776, Thomas Jefferson wrote "United States of America" in a rough draft of the Declaration of Independence, which was adopted by the Second Continental Congress on July 4, 1776.
[src:united-states/united-states-p01] The term "United States" and its initialism "U.S.", used as nouns or as adjectives in English, are common short names for the country.
[src:united-states/united-states-p01] The initialism "USA", a noun, is also common.
[src:united-states/united-states-p01] "United States" and "U.S." are the established terms throughout the U.S. federal government, with prescribed rules.
[src:united-states/united-states-p01] "The States" is an established colloquial shortening of the name, used particularly from abroad; "stateside" is the corresponding adjective or adverb.
[src:united-states/united-states-p01] "America" is the feminine form of the first name of *Americus Vesputius*, the Latinized name of Italian explorer Amerigo Vespucci (1454–1512); it was first used as a place name by the German cartographers Martin Waldseemüller and Matthias Ringmann in 1507.
[src:united-states/united-states-p01] Vespucci proposed that the West Indies discovered by Christopher Columbus in 1492 were part of a previously unknown landmass and not among the Indies at the eastern limit of Asia.
[src:united-states/united-states-p01] In English, the term "America" (used without a qualifier) seldom refers to topics unrelated to the United States.
[src:united-states/united-states-p01] "The Americas" is the general term to describe the totality of the continents of North and South America.
[src:united-states/united-states-p01] The first inhabitants of North America migrated from Siberia approximately 15,000 years ago, either across the Bering land bridge or along the now-submerged Ice Age coastline.
[src:united-states/united-states-p01] The Clovis culture, which appeared around 11,000 BCE in North America, is believed to be the first widespread culture in the Americas.
[src:united-states/united-states-p01] Over time, Indigenous North American cultures grew increasingly sophisticated, and some, such as the Mississippian culture, developed agriculture, architecture, and complex societies.
[src:united-states/united-states-p01] In the post-archaic period, the Mississippian cultures were located in the midwestern, eastern, and southern regions, and the Algonquian in the Great Lakes region and along the Eastern Seaboard, while the Hohokam culture and Ancestral Puebloans inhabited the Southwest.
[src:united-states/united-states-p01] Native population estimates of what is now the United States before the arrival of European colonizers range from around 500,000 to nearly 10 million.
[src:united-states/united-states-p01] Christopher Columbus began exploring the Caribbean for Spain in 1492, leading to Spanish-speaking settlements and missions from what are now Puerto Rico and Florida to New Mexico and California.
[src:united-states/united-states-p01] The first Spanish colony in the present-day continental United States was Spanish Florida, chartered in 1513.
[src:united-states/united-states-p01] After several settlements failed there due to starvation and disease, Spain's first permanent town, Saint Augustine, was founded in 1565.
[src:united-states/united-states-p01] France established its own settlements in French Florida in 1562, but they were either abandoned (Charlesfort, 1578) or destroyed by Spanish raids (Fort Caroline, 1565).
[src:united-states/united-states-p01] Permanent French settlements were founded much later along the Great Lakes (Fort Detroit, 1701), the Mississippi River (St.
[src:united-states/united-states-p01] Louis, 1764) and especially the Gulf of Mexico (New Orleans, 1718).
[src:united-states/united-states-p01] Early European colonies also included the thriving Dutch colony of New Nederland (settled 1626, present-day New York) and the small Swedish colony of New Sweden (settled 1638 in what became Delaware).
[src:united-states/united-states-p01] British colonization of the East Coast began with the Virginia Colony (1607) and the Plymouth Colony (Massachusetts, 1620).
[src:united-states/united-states-p01] The Mayflower Compact in Massachusetts and the Fundamental Orders of Connecticut established precedents for local representative self-governance and constitutionalism that would develop throughout the American colonies.
[src:united-states/united-states-p01] While European settlers in what is now the United States experienced conflicts with Native Americans, they also engaged in trade, exchanging European tools for food and animal pelts.
[src:united-states/united-states-p01] Relations ranged from close cooperation to warfare and massacres.
[src:united-states/united-states-p01] The colonial authorities often pursued policies that forced Native Americans to adopt European lifestyles, including conversion to Christianity.
[src:united-states/united-states-p01] Along the eastern seaboard, settlers trafficked Africans through the Atlantic slave trade, largely to provide manual labor on plantations.
[src:united-states/united-states-p01] The original Thirteen Colonies that would later found the United States were administered as possessions of the British Empire by Crown-appointed governors, though local governments held elections open to most white male property owners.
[src:united-states/united-states-p01] The colonial population grew rapidly from Maine to Georgia, eclipsing Native American populations; by the 1770s, the natural increase of the population was such that only a small minority of Americans had been born overseas.
[src:united-states/united-states-p01] The colonies' distance from Britain facilitated the entrenchment of self-governance, and the First Great Awakening, a series of Christian revivals, fueled colonial interest in guaranteed religious liberty.
[src:united-states/united-states-p01] Following its victory in the French and Indian War, Britain began to assert greater control over local affairs in the Thirteen Colonies, resulting in growing political resistance.
[src:united-states/united-states-p01] One of the primary grievances of the colonists was the denial of their rights as Englishmen, particularly the right to representation in the British government that taxed them.
[src:united-states/united-states-p01] To demonstrate their dissatisfaction and resolve, the First Continental Congress met in 1774 and passed the Continental Association, a colonial boycott of British goods enforced by local "committees of safety" that proved effective.
[src:united-states/united-states-p01] The British attempt to then disarm the colonists resulted in the 1775 Battles of Lexington and Concord, igniting the American Revolutionary War.
[src:united-states/united-states-p01] At the Second Continental Congress, the colonies appointed George Washington Commander-in-Chief of the Continental Army, and created a committee that named Thomas Jefferson to draft the Declaration of Independence.
[src:united-states/united-states-p01] Two days after the Second Continental Congress passed the Lee Resolution to create an independent, sovereign nation, the Declaration was adopted on July 4, 1776.
[src:united-states/united-states-p01] The Founding Fathers of the United States, who included Washington, Jefferson, John Adams, Benjamin Franklin, Alexander Hamilton, John Jay, James Madison, Thomas Paine, and many others, were inspired by Classical, Renaissance, and Enlightenment philosophies and ideas.
[src:united-states/united-states-p01] Though in practical effect since its drafting in 1777, the Articles of Confederation were ratified in 1781 and formally established a decentralized government that operated until 1789.
[src:united-states/united-states-p01] After the British surrender at the siege of Yorktown in 1781, American sovereignty was internationally recognized by the Treaty of Paris (1783), through which the U.S. also gained territory stretching west to the Mississippi River, north to present-day Canada, and south to Spanish Florida.
[src:united-states/united-states-p01] The Northwest Ordinance (1787) established the precedent by which the country's territory would expand with the admission of new states, rather than the expansion of existing states.
[src:united-states/united-states-p01] Constitution was drafted at the 1787 Constitutional Convention to overcome certain limitations of the Articles.
[src:united-states/united-states-p01] It went into effect in 1789, creating a federal republic governed by three separate branches that together formed a system of checks and balances.
[src:united-states/united-states-p01] George Washington was elected the country's first president under the Constitution, and the Bill of Rights (a series of ten amendments to the Constitution) was adopted in 1791 to allay skeptics' concerns about the power of the more centralized government.
[src:united-states/united-states-p01] Washington's resignation as Commander-in-Chief after the Revolutionary War and his later refusal to run for a third term as the country's first president established a precedent for the supremacy of civil authority in the United States and the peaceful transfer of power.
[src:united-states/united-states-p01] In the late 18th century, American settlers began to expand westward in larger numbers, many with a sense of manifest destiny.
[src:united-states/united-states-p01] The Louisiana Purchase of 1803 from France nearly doubled the territory of the United States.
[src:united-states/united-states-p01] Lingering issues with Britain remained, leading to the War of 1812, which was fought to a draw.
[src:united-states/united-states-p01] Spain ceded Florida and its Gulf Coast territory in 1819.
[src:united-states/united-states-p01] The Missouri Compromise of 1820, which admitted Missouri as a slave state and Maine as a free state, attempted to balance the desire of northern states to prevent the expansion of slavery into new territories with that of southern states to extend it there.
[src:united-states/united-states-p01] Primarily, the compromise prohibited slavery in all other lands of the Louisiana Purchase north of the 36°30′ parallel.
[src:united-states/united-states-p01] As Americans expanded further into territory inhabited by Native Americans, the federal government implemented policies of Indian removal or assimilation.
[src:united-states/united-states-p01] The most significant such legislation was the Indian Removal Act of 1830, a key policy of President Andrew Jackson.
[src:united-states/united-states-p01] It resulted in the Trail of Tears (1830–1850), in which an estimated 60,000 Native Americans living east of the Mississippi River were forcibly removed and displaced to lands far to the west, causing 13,200 to 16,700 deaths along the forced march.
[src:united-states/united-states-p01] Settler expansion as well as this influx of Indigenous peoples from the East resulted in the American Indian Wars west of the Mississippi.
[src:united-states/united-states-p01] During the colonial period, slavery became legal in all the Thirteen colonies, and by 1770 it provided the main labor force in the large-scale, agriculture-dependent economies of the Southern Colonies from Maryland to Georgia.
[src:united-states/united-states-p01] The practice began to be significantly questioned during the American Revolution, and spurred by an active abolitionist movement that had reemerged in the 1830s, states in the North enacted laws to prohibit slavery within their boundaries.
[src:united-states/united-states-p01] At the same time, support for slavery had strengthened in Southern states, with widespread use of inventions such as the cotton gin (1793) having made slavery immensely profitable for Southern elites.
[src:united-states/united-states-p01] The United States annexed the Republic of Texas in 1845, and the 1846 Oregon Treaty led to U.S. control of the present-day American Northwest.
[src:united-states/united-states-p01] Dispute with Mexico over Texas led to the Mexican–American War (1846–1848).
[src:united-states/united-states-p01] After the victory of the U.S., Mexico recognized U.S. sovereignty over Texas, New Mexico, and California in the 1848 Mexican Cession; the cession's lands also included the future states of Nevada, Colorado and Utah.
[src:united-states/united-states-p01] The California gold rush of 1848–1849 spurred a huge migration of white settlers to the Pacific coast, leading to even more confrontations with Native populations.
[src:united-states/united-states-p01] One of the most violent, the California genocide of thousands of Native inhabitants, lasted into the mid-1870s.
[src:united-states/united-states-p01] Additional western territories and states were created.
[src:united-states/united-states-p01] Throughout the 1850s, the sectional conflict regarding slavery was further inflamed by national legislation in the U.S.
[src:united-states/united-states-p01] Congress and decisions of the Supreme Court.
[src:united-states/united-states-p01] In Congress, the Fugitive Slave Act of 1850 mandated the forcible return to their enslavers in the South of persons taking refuge in non-slave states, while the Kansas–Nebraska Act of 1854 effectively gutted the anti-slavery requirements of the Missouri Compromise.
[src:united-states/united-states-p01] In its Dred Scott decision of 1857, the Supreme Court ruled against an enslaved person brought into non-slave territory, simultaneously declaring the entire Missouri Compromise to be unconstitutional.
[src:united-states/united-states-p01] These and other events exacerbated tensions between North and South that would culminate in the American Civil War (1861–1865).
[src:united-states/united-states-p01] Beginning with South Carolina, 11 slave-state governments voted to secede from the United States in 1861, joining to create the Confederate States of America.
[src:united-states/united-states-p01] All other state governments remained loyal to the Union.
[src:united-states/united-states-p01] War broke out in April 1861 after the Confederacy bombarded Fort Sumter.
[src:united-states/united-states-p01] Following the Emancipation Proclamation on January 1, 1863, many freed slaves joined the Union army.
[src:united-states/united-states-p01] The war began to turn in the Union's favor following the 1863 Siege of Vicksburg and Battle of Gettysburg, and the Confederates surrendered in 1865 after the Union's victory in the Battle of Appomattox Court House.
[src:united-states/united-states-p01] Efforts toward reconstruction in the secessionist South had begun as early as 1862, but it was only after President Lincoln's assassination that the three Reconstruction Amendments to the Constitution were ratified to protect civil rights.
[src:united-states/united-states-p01] The amendments codified nationally the abolition of slavery and involuntary servitude except as punishment for crimes, promised equal protection under the law for all persons, and prohibited discrimination on the basis of race or previous enslavement.
[src:united-states/united-states-p01] As a result, African Americans took an active political role in ex-Confederate states in the decade following the Civil War.
[src:united-states/united-states-p01] The former Confederate states were readmitted to the Union, beginning with Tennessee in 1866 and ending with Georgia in 1870.
[src:united-states/united-states-p01] National infrastructure, including transcontinental telegraph and railroads, spurred growth in the American frontier.
[src:united-states/united-states-p01] This was accelerated by the Homestead Acts, through which nearly 10 percent of the total land area of the United States was given away free to some 1.6 million homesteaders.
[src:united-states/united-states-p01] From 1865 through 1917, an unprecedented stream of immigrants arrived in the United States, including 24.4 million from Europe.
[src:united-states/united-states-p01] Most came through the Port of New York, as New York City and other major cities on the East Coast became home to large Jewish, Irish, and Italian populations.
[src:united-states/united-states-p01] Many Northern Europeans as well as significant numbers of Germans and other Central Europeans moved to the Midwest.
[src:united-states/united-states-p01] At the same time, about one million French Canadians migrated from Quebec to New England.
[src:united-states/united-states-p01] During the Great Migration, millions of African Americans left the rural South for urban areas in the North.
[src:united-states/united-states-p01] Alaska was purchased from Russia in 1867.
[src:united-states/united-states-p01] The Compromise of 1877 is generally considered the end of the Reconstruction era, as it resolved the electoral crisis following the 1876 presidential election and led President Rutherford B.
[src:united-states/united-states-p01] Hayes to reduce the role of federal troops in the South.
[src:united-states/united-states-p01] Immediately, the Redeemers began evicting the Carpetbaggers and quickly regained local control of Southern politics in the name of white supremacy.
[src:united-states/united-states-p01] African Americans endured a period of heightened, overt racism following Reconstruction, a time often considered the nadir of American race relations.
[src:united-states/united-states-p01] A series of Supreme Court decisions, including *Plessy v.
[src:united-states/united-states-p01] An explosion of technological advancement, accompanied by the exploitation of cheap immigrant labor, led to rapid economic expansion during the Gilded Age of the late 19th century.
[src:united-states/united-states-p01] It continued into the early 20th, when the United States already outpaced the economies of Britain, France, and Germany combined.
[src:united-states/united-states-p01] Tycoons led the nation's expansion in the railroad, petroleum, and steel industries, as the United States emerged as a pioneer of the automotive industry.
[src:united-states/united-states-p01] This fostered the amassing of enormous economic and political power by a few prominent industrialists, largely through the formation of trusts and monopolies to prevent competition.
[src:united-states/united-states-p01] These changes resulted in significant increases in economic inequality, slum conditions, and social unrest, creating a fertile environment for labor unions to flourish and, to a more limited extent, socialist movements.
[src:united-states/united-states-p01] This period eventually ended with the advent of the Progressive Era, which was characterized by significant economic, legislative and social reforms.
[src:united-states/united-states-p01] Pro-American elements in Hawaii overthrew the Hawaiian monarchy; the islands were annexed in 1898.
[src:united-states/united-states-p01] That same year, Puerto Rico, the Philippines, and Guam were ceded to the U.S. by Spain after the latter's defeat in the Spanish–American War.
[src:united-states/united-states-p01] (The Philippines was granted full independence from the U.S. on July 4, 1946, following World War II.
[src:united-states/united-states-p01] Puerto Rico and Guam have remained U.S. territories.) American Samoa was acquired by the United States in 1900 after the Second Samoan Civil War.
[src:united-states/united-states-p01] Virgin Islands were purchased from Denmark in 1917 after Danish voters approved the sale in a 1916 referendum.
[src:united-states/united-states-p01] The United States entered World War I alongside the Allies in 1917 helping to turn the tide against the Central Powers.
[src:united-states/united-states-p01] In 1920, a constitutional amendment granted nationwide women's suffrage.
[src:united-states/united-states-p01] During the 1920s and 1930s, radio for mass communication and early television transformed communications nationwide.
[src:united-states/united-states-p01] The Wall Street Crash of 1929 had triggered the Great Depression, to which President Franklin D.
[src:united-states/united-states-p01] Roosevelt responded with the New Deal plan of "reform, recovery and relief", a series of unprecedented and sweeping recovery programs and employment relief projects combined with financial reforms and regulations.
[src:united-states/united-states-p01] Initially neutral during World War II, the U.S. began supplying war materiel to the Allies of World War II in March 1941 and entered the war in December after Japan's attack on Pearl Harbor.
[src:united-states/united-states-p01] Agreeing to a "Europe first" policy, the U.S. concentrated its wartime efforts on Japan's allies Italy and Germany until their final defeat in May 1945.
[src:united-states/united-states-p01] The U.S. developed the first nuclear weapons and used them against the Japanese cities of Hiroshima and Nagasaki in August 1945, ending the war.
[src:united-states/united-states-p01] The United States was one of the "Four Policemen" who met to plan the post-war world, alongside the United Kingdom, the Soviet Union, and China.
[src:united-states/united-states-p01] The U.S. emerged relatively unscathed from the war, with even greater economic power and international political influence.
[src:united-states/united-states-p01] The end of World War II in 1945 left the U.S. and the Soviet Union as superpowers, each with its own political, military, and economic sphere of influence.
[src:united-states/united-states-p01] Geopolitical tensions between the two superpowers soon led to the Cold War.
[src:united-states/united-states-p01] The U.S. implemented a policy of containment intended to limit the Soviet Union's sphere of influence; engaged in regime change against governments perceived to be aligned with the Soviets; and prevailed in the Space Race, which culminated with the first crewed Moon landing in 1969.
[src:united-states/united-states-p01] Domestically, the U.S. experienced economic growth, urbanization, and population growth following World War II.
[src:united-states/united-states-p01] The civil rights movement emerged, with Martin Luther King Jr. becoming a prominent leader in the early 1960s.
[src:united-states/united-states-p01] The Great Society plan of President Lyndon B.
[src:united-states/united-states-p01] Johnson's administration resulted in groundbreaking and broad-reaching laws, policies and a constitutional amendment to counteract some of the worst effects of lingering institutional racism.
[src:united-states/united-states-p01] The counterculture movement in the U.S. brought significant social changes, including the liberalization of attitudes toward recreational drug use and sexuality.
[src:united-states/united-states-p01] It also encouraged open defiance of the military draft (leading to the end of conscription in 1973) and wide opposition to U.S. intervention in Vietnam, with the U.S. totally withdrawing in 1975.
[src:united-states/united-states-p01] A societal shift in the roles of women was significantly responsible for the large increase in female paid labor participation starting in the 1970s, and by 1985 the majority of American women aged 16 and older were employed.
[src:united-states/united-states-p01] The Fall of Communism and the dissolution of the Soviet Union from 1989 to 1991 marked the end of the Cold War and left the United States as the world's sole superpower.
[src:united-states/united-states-p01] This cemented the United States' global influence, reinforcing the concept of the "American Century" as the U.S. dominated international political, cultural, economic, and military affairs.
[src:united-states/united-states-p01] The 1990s saw the longest recorded economic expansion in American history, a dramatic decline in U.S. crime rates, and advances in technology.
[src:united-states/united-states-p01] Throughout this decade, technological innovations such as the World Wide Web, the evolution of the Pentium microprocessor in accordance with Moore's law, rechargeable lithium-ion batteries, the first gene therapy trial, and cloning either emerged in the U.S. or were improved upon there.
[src:united-states/united-states-p01] In the 1990s, the Human Genome Project was launched, while Nasdaq became the first stock market in the United States to trade online.
[src:united-states/united-states-p01] In the Gulf War of 1991, an American-led international coalition of states expelled an Iraqi invasion force that had occupied neighboring Kuwait.
[src:united-states/united-states-p01] The September 11 attacks on the United States in 2001 by the pan-Islamist militant organization al-Qaeda led to the war on terror and subsequent military interventions in Afghanistan and Iraq.
[src:united-states/united-states-p01] The U.S. housing bubble culminated in 2007 with the Great Recession, the largest economic contraction since the Great Depression.
[src:united-states/united-states-p01] Beginning in the 2010s, and accelerating in the 2020s, the United States has experienced increased political polarization and significant democratic backsliding.
[src:united-states/united-states-p01] The country's polarization was violently reflected in the January 2021 Capitol attack, when a mob of insurrectionists supporting President Donald Trump entered the U.S.
[src:united-states/united-states-p01] Capitol and sought to prevent the peaceful transfer of power in an attempted self-coup d'état.
[src:united-states/united-states-p01] It was the first presidential refusal of the peaceful transfer of power.
[src:united-states/united-states-p01] Scholars have broadly classified the United States as transitioning from a liberal democratic polity to a hybrid regime since 2025.
[src:united-states/united-states-p01] By 2026, a poll by the London School of Economics found that a majority of political scientists surveyed did not believe that the 2026 United States elections would meet the criteria of being "free and fair".
[src:united-states/united-states-p01] The United States is the world's third-largest country by total area behind Russia and Canada.
[src:united-states/united-states-p01] The 48 contiguous states and the District of Columbia have a combined area of 3,119,885 square miles (8,080,470 km2).
[src:united-states/united-states-p01] In 2021, the United States had 8% of the Earth's permanent meadows and pastures and 10% of its cropland.
[src:united-states/united-states-p01] Starting in the east, the coastal plain of the Atlantic seaboard gives way to inland forests and rolling hills in the Piedmont plateau region.
[src:united-states/united-states-p01] The Appalachian Mountains and the Adirondack Massif separate the East Coast from the Great Lakes and the grasslands of the Midwest.
[src:united-states/united-states-p01] The Mississippi River System, the world's fourth-longest river system, runs predominantly north–south through the center of the country.
[src:united-states/united-states-p01] The flat and fertile prairie of the Great Plains stretches to the west, interrupted by a highland region in the southeast.
[src:united-states/united-states-p01] The Rocky Mountains, west of the Great Plains, extend north to south across the country, peaking at over 14,000 feet (4,300 m) in Colorado.
[src:united-states/united-states-p01] The supervolcano underlying Yellowstone National Park in the Rocky Mountains, the Yellowstone Caldera, is the continent's largest volcanic feature.
[src:united-states/united-states-p01] Farther west are the rocky Great Basin and the Chihuahuan, Sonoran, and Mojave deserts.
[src:united-states/united-states-p01] In the northwest corner of Arizona, carved by the Colorado River, is the Grand Canyon, a steep-sided canyon and popular tourist destination known for its overwhelming visual size and intricate, colorful landscape.
[src:united-states/united-states-p01] The Cascade and Sierra Nevada mountain ranges run close to the Pacific coast.
[src:united-states/united-states-p01] The lowest and highest points in the contiguous United States are in the State of California, about 84 miles (135 km) apart.
[src:united-states/united-states-p01] At an elevation of 20,310 feet (6,190.5 m), Alaska's Denali (also called Mount McKinley) is the highest peak in the country and on the continent.
[src:united-states/united-states-p01] Active volcanoes in the U.S. are common throughout Alaska's Alexander and Aleutian Islands.
[src:united-states/united-states-p01] Located entirely outside North America, the archipelago of Hawaii consists of volcanic islands, physiographically and ethnologically part of the Polynesian subregion of Oceania.
[src:united-states/united-states-p01] In addition to its total land area, the United States has one of the world's largest marine exclusive economic zones spanning approximately 4.5 million square miles (11.7 million km2) of ocean.
[src:united-states/united-states-p01] With its large size and geographic variety, the United States includes most climate types.
[src:united-states/united-states-p01] East of the 100th meridian, the climate ranges from humid continental in the north to humid subtropical in the south.
[src:united-states/united-states-p01] Many mountainous areas of the American West have an alpine climate.
[src:united-states/united-states-p01] The climate is arid in the Southwest, Mediterranean in coastal California, and oceanic in coastal Oregon, Washington, and southern Alaska.
[src:united-states/united-states-p01] Hawaii, the southern tip of Florida and U.S. territories in the Caribbean and Pacific are tropical.
[src:united-states/united-states-p01] The United States receives more high-impact extreme weather incidents than any other country.
[src:united-states/united-states-p01] States bordering the Gulf of Mexico are prone to hurricanes, and most of the world's tornadoes occur in the country, mainly in Tornado Alley.
[src:united-states/united-states-p01] Due to climate change, extreme weather has become more frequent in the U.S. in the 21st century, with three times the number of reported heat waves compared to the 1960s.
[src:united-states/united-states-p01] Since the 1990s, droughts in the American Southwest have become more persistent and more severe.
[src:united-states/united-states-p01] The regions considered as the most attractive to the population are the most vulnerable.
[src:united-states/united-states-p01] The U.S. is one of 17 megadiverse countries containing large numbers of endemic species: about 17,000 species of vascular plants occur in the contiguous United States and Alaska, and over 1,800 species of flowering plants are found in Hawaii, few of which occur on the mainland.
[src:united-states/united-states-p01] The United States is home to 428 mammal species, 784 birds, 311 reptiles, 295 amphibians, and around 91,000 insect species.
[src:united-states/united-states-p01] There are 63 national parks, and hundreds of other federally managed monuments, forests, and wilderness areas, administered by the National Park Service and other agencies.
[src:united-states/united-states-p01] About 28% of the country's land is publicly owned and federally managed, primarily in the Western States.
[src:united-states/united-states-p01] Most of this land is protected, though some is leased for commercial use, and less than one percent is used for military purposes.
[src:united-states/united-states-p01] Environmental issues in the United States include debates on non-renewable resources and nuclear energy, air and water pollution, biodiversity, logging and deforestation, and climate change.
[src:united-states/united-states-p01] Environmental Protection Agency (EPA) is the federal agency charged with addressing most environmental-related issues.
[src:united-states/united-states-p01] The idea of wilderness has shaped the management of public lands since 1964, with the Wilderness Act.
[src:united-states/united-states-p01] The Endangered Species Act of 1973 provides a way to protect threatened and endangered species and their habitats.
[src:united-states/united-states-p01] The United States Fish and Wildlife Service implements and enforces the Act.
[src:united-states/united-states-p01] In 2024, the U.S. ranked 35th among 180 countries in the Environmental Performance Index.
[src:united-states/united-states-p02] The United States is a federal republic consisting of 50 states and a federal capital district, Washington, D.C.
[src:united-states/united-states-p02] The U.S. asserts sovereignty over five unincorporated territories and several uninhabited island possessions.
[src:united-states/united-states-p02] It is the world's oldest surviving federation, and its presidential system of federal government has been adopted, in whole or in part, by many newly independent states worldwide following their decolonization.
[src:united-states/united-states-p02] The Constitution of the United States serves as the country's supreme legal document.
[src:united-states/united-states-p02] The United States was the most prominent liberal democracy for much of the 20th and early 21st centuries, but has undergone significant democratic backsliding and a shift toward a hybrid regime—a political system combining autocratic and democratic features.
[src:united-states/united-states-p02] Gerrymandering, the manipulation of districts for political advantage, is widespread and has been driven by 2010s and 2020s Supreme Court rulings.
[src:united-states/united-states-p02] There is an ongoing debate among political scientists on whether the country is more appropriately classified as an electoral autocracy or illiberal democracy, with few still considering it to meet the criteria of a robust liberal democracy.
[src:united-states/united-states-p02] Composed of three branches, all headquartered in Washington, D.C., the federal government is the national government of the United States.
[src:united-states/united-states-p02] Constitution establishes a separation of powers intended to provide a system of checks and balances to prevent any of the three branches from becoming supreme.
[src:united-states/united-states-p02] The three-branch system is known as the presidential system, in contrast to the parliamentary system where the executive is part of the legislative body.
[src:united-states/united-states-p02] Many countries around the world adopted this aspect of the 1789 Constitution of the United States, especially in the postcolonial Americas.
[src:united-states/united-states-p02] Congress is a bicameral legislature made up of the Senate and the House of Representatives.
[src:united-states/united-states-p02] The Senate has 100 members—two residents from each state and elected by that state's voters for a six-year term.
[src:united-states/united-states-p02] The House of Representatives has 435 members, elected for a two-year term by the constituency of the congressional district where they reside.
[src:united-states/united-states-p02] A state's legislature decides the district boundaries, which are contiguous within the state.
[src:united-states/united-states-p02] Every U.S. congressional district is of equivalent population and sends one representative to Congress.
[src:united-states/united-states-p02] Election years for senators are staggered so that only one-third of them will be up for election every two years.
[src:united-states/united-states-p02] U.S. representatives are all up for election at the same time every two years.
[src:united-states/united-states-p02] Congress makes federal law, declares war, approves treaties, has the power of the purse, and has the power of impeachment.
[src:united-states/united-states-p02] One of its foremost non-legislative functions is the power to investigate and oversee the executive branch.
[src:united-states/united-states-p02] Congressional oversight is usually delegated to committees and is facilitated by Congress' power to issue subpoenas.
[src:united-states/united-states-p02] Much of the work of Congress is performed by a collection of committees, each appointed for a specific purpose or function.
[src:united-states/united-states-p02] Committee membership is by tradition and statute bipartisan, but all committees are chaired by a member of the majority party, who sets the committee agenda.
[src:united-states/united-states-p02] The U.S. president is the head of state, commander-in-chief of the military, and chief executive of the federal government.
[src:united-states/united-states-p02] The president appoints the members of the Cabinet, subject to Senate approval, and names other officials who administer and enforce federal law and policy through their respective agencies.
[src:united-states/united-states-p02] The president has the ability to veto legislative bills from the U.S.
[src:united-states/united-states-p02] However, presidential vetoes can be overridden by a two-thirds supermajority vote in both chambers of Congress.
[src:united-states/united-states-p02] The president also has clemency power for federal crimes and can issue pardons.
[src:united-states/united-states-p02] Finally, the president has the authority to issue expansive "executive orders" in a number of policy areas, subject to judicial review.
[src:united-states/united-states-p02] Candidates for president typically campaign with a vice-presidential running mate, and both candidates are typically elected together, or defeated together, in a presidential election.
[src:united-states/united-states-p02] Unlike other votes in American politics, this is technically an indirect election in which the winner will be determined by the U.S.
[src:united-states/united-states-p02] There, votes are officially cast by individual electors selected by their state legislature.
[src:united-states/united-states-p02] In practice, however, each of the 50 states chooses a group of presidential electors who are required by state law to confirm the winner of their state's popular vote.
[src:united-states/united-states-p02] Each state is allocated two electors plus one additional elector for every congressional district in the state, which in effect combines to equal the number of elected officials that state sends to Congress.
[src:united-states/united-states-p02] The District of Columbia, with no representatives or senators, is allocated three electoral votes.
[src:united-states/united-states-p02] Both the president and the vice president serve a four-year term, and the president may be reelected to the office only once, for one additional four-year term.
[src:united-states/united-states-p02] The U.S. federal judiciary, whose judges are all appointed for life by the president with Senate approval, consists primarily of the U.S.
[src:united-states/united-states-p02] Supreme Court, the U.S. courts of appeals, and the U.S. district courts.
[src:united-states/united-states-p02] The lowest level in the federal judiciary is the federal district court, which decides all cases considered to be under "original jurisdiction", such as federal statutes, constitutional law, or international treaties.
[src:united-states/united-states-p02] After a federal district court has decided a case, its ruling may be contested and sent to a higher court, a federal court of appeals.
[src:united-states/united-states-p02] The U.S. judicial system's 12 federal circuits divide the country into 12 separate geographic administrative regions for appeals decisions.
[src:united-states/united-states-p02] The next and highest court in the system is the Supreme Court of the United States.
[src:united-states/united-states-p02] Supreme Court interprets laws and overturns those it finds unconstitutional.
[src:united-states/united-states-p02] On average, the Supreme Court receives about 7,000 appeals petitions for writs of certiorari each year, but only grants about 80.
[src:united-states/united-states-p02] Consisting of nine members led by the Chief Justice of the United States, the court usually judges each case before it by majority decision.
[src:united-states/united-states-p02] In the case of an impeachment trial in the Senate of a sitting president, the chief justice presides.
[src:united-states/united-states-p02] As with all other federal judges, the members are appointed for life by the sitting president with Senate approval when a vacancy becomes available.
[src:united-states/united-states-p02] In the U.S. federal system, sovereign powers are shared between three levels of government specified in the Constitution: the federal government, the states, and Indian tribes.
[src:united-states/united-states-p02] The U.S. also asserts sovereignty over five permanently inhabited territories: American Samoa, Guam, the Northern Mariana Islands, Puerto Rico, and the U.S.
[src:united-states/united-states-p02] Residents of the 50 states are governed by their elected state government, under state constitutions compatible with the national constitution, and by elected local governments that are administrative divisions of a state.
[src:united-states/united-states-p02] States are subdivided into counties or county equivalents, which (except in Hawaii) can permit the formation of independent municipalities administered by their own elected representatives.
[src:united-states/united-states-p02] The District of Columbia is a federal district containing the U.S. capital, Washington, D.C.
[src:united-states/united-states-p02] The federal district is an administrative division of the federal government.
[src:united-states/united-states-p02] Indian country is made up of 574 federally recognized tribes and 326 Indian reservations.
[src:united-states/united-states-p02] They hold a government-to-government relationship with the U.S. federal government in Washington and are legally defined as domestic dependent nations with inherent tribal sovereignty rights.
[src:united-states/united-states-p02] In addition to the five major territories, the U.S. also asserts sovereignty over the United States Minor Outlying Islands in the Pacific Ocean and the Caribbean.
[src:united-states/united-states-p02] The seven undisputed islands without permanent populations are Baker Island, Howland Island, Jarvis Island, Johnston Atoll, Kingman Reef, Midway Atoll, and Palmyra Atoll.
[src:united-states/united-states-p02] U.S. sovereignty over the unpopulated Bajo Nuevo Bank, Navassa Island, Serranilla Bank, and Wake Island is disputed.
[src:united-states/united-states-p02] The Constitution is silent on political parties.
[src:united-states/united-states-p02] However, they developed independently in the 18th century with the Federalist and Anti-Federalist parties.
[src:united-states/united-states-p02] Since then, the United States has operated as a *de facto* two-party system, though the parties have changed over time.
[src:united-states/united-states-p02] Since the mid-19th century, the two main national parties have been the Democratic Party and the Republican Party.
[src:united-states/united-states-p02] The United States has an established structure of foreign relations, with the world's second-largest diplomatic corps as of 2024.
[src:united-states/united-states-p02] It is a permanent member of the United Nations Security Council and home to the United Nations headquarters.
[src:united-states/united-states-p02] The United States is a member of the G7, G20, and OECD intergovernmental organizations.
[src:united-states/united-states-p02] Almost all countries have embassies and many have consulates (official representatives) in the country.
[src:united-states/united-states-p02] Likewise, nearly all countries host formal diplomatic missions with the United States, except Iran, North Korea, and Bhutan.
[src:united-states/united-states-p02] Though Taiwan does not have formal diplomatic relations with the U.S., it maintains close unofficial relations.
[src:united-states/united-states-p02] The United States regularly supplies Taiwan with military equipment to deter potential Chinese aggression.
[src:united-states/united-states-p02] The country's geopolitical attention has increasingly turned to the Indo-Pacific, where the U.S. joined the Quadrilateral Security Dialogue and AUKUS.
[src:united-states/united-states-p02] The United States has a "Special Relationship" with the United Kingdom and strong ties with Canada, Australia, New Zealand, the Philippines, Japan, South Korea, Israel, and several European Union countries such as France, Italy, Germany, Spain, and Poland.
[src:united-states/united-states-p02] The U.S. works closely with its NATO allies on military and national security issues, and with countries in the Americas through the Organization of American States and the United States–Mexico–Canada Free Trade Agreement.
[src:united-states/united-states-p02] The U.S. exercises full international defense authority and responsibility for Micronesia, the Marshall Islands, and Palau through the Compact of Free Association.
[src:united-states/united-states-p02] It has increasingly conducted strategic cooperation with India, while its ties with China have steadily deteriorated.
[src:united-states/united-states-p02] Beginning in 2014, the U.S. had become a key ally of Ukraine.
[src:united-states/united-states-p02] The president is the commander-in-chief of the United States Armed Forces and appoints its leaders, the secretary of defense and the Joint Chiefs of Staff.
[src:united-states/united-states-p02] The Department of Defense, headquartered at the Pentagon near Washington, D.C., administers five of the six service branches, which are made up of the U.S.
[src:united-states/united-states-p02] Army, Marine Corps, Navy, Air Force, and Space Force.
[src:united-states/united-states-p02] The Coast Guard is administered by the Department of Homeland Security in peacetime and can be transferred to the Department of the Navy in wartime.
[src:united-states/united-states-p02] Total strength of the entire military is about 1.3 million active duty with an additional 400,000 in reserve.
[src:united-states/united-states-p02] The United States military is widely regarded as the most powerful and advanced in the world.
[src:united-states/united-states-p02] The U.S. spent $954 billion on its military in 2025, which is by far the largest amount of any country, making up 33% of global military spending and accounting for 3.1% of the country's GDP.
[src:united-states/united-states-p02] The U.S. possesses 42% of the world's nuclear weapons—the second-largest stockpile after that of Russia.
[src:united-states/united-states-p02] The United States has the third-largest combined armed forces in the world, behind the Chinese People's Liberation Army and Indian Armed Forces.
[src:united-states/united-states-p02] In addition to the vast network of military bases on its soil, the U.S. maintains approximately 800 other bases and installations around the world, and it deploys greater than 100 active-duty personnel in each of 25 foreign countries.
[src:united-states/united-states-p02] The United States has engaged in over 400 military interventions since its founding in 1776, with over half of these occurring between 1950 and 2019 and 25% occurring in the post–Cold War era.
[src:united-states/united-states-p02] State defense forces (SDFs) are military units that operate under the sole authority of a state government.
[src:united-states/united-states-p02] SDFs are authorized by state and federal law but are under the command of the state's governor.
[src:united-states/united-states-p02] National Guard organizations fall under the dual control of state or territorial governments and the federal government; their units can also become federalized entities, but SDFs cannot be federalized.
[src:united-states/united-states-p02] The National Guard personnel of a state or territory can be federalized by the president under the National Defense Act Amendments of 1933; this legislation created the Guard and provides for the integration of Army National Guard and Air National Guard units and personnel into the U.S.
[src:united-states/united-states-p02] The total number of National Guard members is about 430,000, while the estimated combined strength of SDFs is less than 10,000.
[src:united-states/united-states-p02] There are about 18,000 U.S. police agencies from local to national level in the United States.
[src:united-states/united-states-p02] Law in the United States is mainly enforced by local police departments and sheriff departments in their municipal or county jurisdictions.
[src:united-states/united-states-p02] The state police departments have authority in their respective state, and federal agencies such as the Federal Bureau of Investigation (FBI) and the U.S.
[src:united-states/united-states-p02] Marshals Service have national jurisdiction and specialized duties, such as protecting civil rights, national security, enforcing U.S. federal courts' rulings and federal laws, and interstate criminal activity.
[src:united-states/united-states-p02] State courts conduct almost all civil and criminal trials, while federal courts adjudicate the much smaller number of civil and criminal cases that relate to federal law.
[src:united-states/united-states-p02] There is no unified "criminal justice system" in the United States.
[src:united-states/united-states-p02] The American prison system is largely heterogenous, with thousands of relatively independent systems operating across federal, state, local, and tribal levels.
[src:united-states/united-states-p02] Despite disparate systems of confinement, four main institutions dominate: federal prisons, state prisons, local jails, and juvenile correctional facilities.
[src:united-states/united-states-p02] Federal prisons are run by the Federal Bureau of Prisons and hold pretrial detainees as well as people who have been convicted of federal crimes.
[src:united-states/united-states-p02] State prisons, run by the department of corrections of each state, hold people sentenced and serving prison time (usually longer than one year) for felony offenses.
[src:united-states/united-states-p02] Local jails are county or municipal facilities that incarcerate defendants prior to trial; they also hold those serving short sentences (typically under a year).
[src:united-states/united-states-p02] Juvenile correctional facilities are operated by local or state governments and serve as longer-term placements for any minor adjudicated as delinquent and ordered by a judge to be confined.
[src:united-states/united-states-p02] In January 2023, the United States had the sixth-highest per capita incarceration rate in the world—531 people per 100,000 inhabitants—and the largest prison and jail population in the world, with more than 1.9 million people incarcerated.
[src:united-states/united-states-p02] An analysis of the World Health Organization Mortality Database from 2010 showed U.S. homicide rates "were 7 times higher than in other high-income countries, driven by a gun homicide rate that was 25 times higher".
[src:united-states/united-states-p02] The country's legal system is classified by some political scientists and legal scholars as operating under a "partial rule of law" system, according to two 2026 surveys conducted by Bright Line Watch and the London School of Economics.
[src:united-states/united-states-p02] The U.S. has a highly developed mixed economy that has been the world's largest nominally since about 1890.
[src:united-states/united-states-p02] Its 2024 gross domestic product (GDP) of more than $29 trillion constituted over 25% of nominal global economic output, or 15% at purchasing power parity (PPP).
[src:united-states/united-states-p02] From 1983 to 2008, U.S. real compounded annual GDP growth was 3.3%, compared to a 2.3% weighted average for the rest of the G7.
[src:united-states/united-states-p02] The country ranks first in the world by nominal GDP, second when adjusted for purchasing power parities (PPP), and ninth by PPP-adjusted GDP per capita.
[src:united-states/united-states-p02] In February 2024, the total U.S. federal government debt was $34.4 trillion.
[src:united-states/united-states-p02] Of the world's 500 largest companies by revenue, 138 were headquartered in the U.S. in 2025, the highest number of any country.
[src:united-states/united-states-p02] The U.S. dollar is the currency most used in international transactions and the world's foremost reserve currency, backed by the country's dominant economy, its military, the petrodollar system, its large U.S. treasuries market, and its linked eurodollar.
[src:united-states/united-states-p02] Several countries use it as their official currency, and in others it is the *de facto* currency.
[src:united-states/united-states-p02] The U.S. has free trade agreements with several countries, including the USMCA.
[src:united-states/united-states-p02] Although the United States has reached a post-industrial level of economic development and is often described as having a service economy, it remains a major industrial power; in 2024, the U.S. manufacturing sector was the world's second-largest by value output after China's.
[src:united-states/united-states-p02] New York City is the world's principal financial center, and its metropolitan area is the world's largest metropolitan economy.
[src:united-states/united-states-p02] The New York Stock Exchange and Nasdaq, both located in New York City, are the world's two largest stock exchanges by market capitalization and trade volume.
[src:united-states/united-states-p02] The United States is at the forefront of technological advancement and innovation in many economic fields, especially in artificial intelligence; electronics and computers; pharmaceuticals; and medical, aerospace and military equipment.
[src:united-states/united-states-p02] The country's economy is fueled by abundant natural resources, a well-developed infrastructure, and high productivity.
[src:united-states/united-states-p02] The largest trading partners of the United States are the European Union, Mexico, Canada, China, Japan, South Korea, the United Kingdom, Vietnam, India, and Taiwan.
[src:united-states/united-states-p02] The United States is the world's largest importer and second-largest exporter.
[src:united-states/united-states-p02] It is by far the world's largest exporter of services.
[src:united-states/united-states-p02] Americans have the highest average household and employee income among OECD member states, and the fourth-highest median household income in 2023, up from sixth-highest in 2013.
[src:united-states/united-states-p02] With personal consumption expenditures of over $18.5 trillion in 2023, the U.S. has a heavily consumer-driven economy and is the world's largest consumer market.
[src:united-states/united-states-p02] The U.S. ranked first in the number of dollar billionaires and millionaires in 2023, with 735 billionaires and nearly 22 million millionaires.
[src:united-states/united-states-p02] Wealth in the United States is highly concentrated; in 2011, the richest 10% of the adult population owned 72% of the country's household wealth, while the bottom 50% owned just 2%.
[src:united-states/united-states-p02] U.S. wealth inequality increased substantially since the late 1980s, and income inequality in the U.S. reached a record high in 2019.
[src:united-states/united-states-p02] In 2024, the country had some of the highest wealth and income inequality levels among OECD countries.
[src:united-states/united-states-p02] Since the 1970s, there has been a decoupling of U.S. wage gains from worker productivity.
[src:united-states/united-states-p02] In 2016, the top fifth of earners took home more than half of all income, giving the U.S. one of the widest income distributions among OECD countries.
[src:united-states/united-states-p02] There were about 771,480 homeless persons in the U.S. in 2024.
[src:united-states/united-states-p02] In 2022, 6.4 million children experienced food insecurity.
[src:united-states/united-states-p02] Feeding America estimates that around one in five, or approximately 13 million, children experience hunger in the U.S. and do not know where or when they will get their next meal.
[src:united-states/united-states-p02] Also in 2022, about 37.9 million people, or 11.5% of the U.S. population, were living in poverty.
[src:united-states/united-states-p02] The United States has a smaller welfare state and redistributes less income through government action than most other high-income countries.
[src:united-states/united-states-p02] It is the only advanced economy that does not guarantee its workers paid vacation nationally and one of a few countries in the world without federal paid family leave as a legal right.
[src:united-states/united-states-p02] The United States has a higher percentage of low-income workers than almost any other developed country, largely because of a weak collective bargaining system and lack of government support for at-risk workers.
[src:united-states/united-states-p02] The United States has been a leader in technological innovation since the late 19th century and scientific research since the mid-20th century.
[src:united-states/united-states-p02] Methods for producing interchangeable parts and the establishment of a machine tool industry enabled the large-scale manufacturing of U.S. consumer products in the late 19th century.
[src:united-states/united-states-p02] By the early 20th century, factory electrification, the introduction of the assembly line, and other labor-saving techniques created the system of mass production.
[src:united-states/united-states-p02] In the 21st century, the United States continues to be one of the world's foremost scientific powers, though China has emerged as a major competitor in many fields.
[src:united-states/united-states-p02] The U.S. has the highest research and development expenditures of any country and ranks ninth as a percentage of GDP.
[src:united-states/united-states-p02] In 2022, the United States was (after China) the country with the second-highest number of published scientific papers.
[src:united-states/united-states-p02] In 2021, the U.S. ranked second (also after China) by the number of patent applications, and third by trademark and industrial design applications (after China and Germany), according to World Intellectual Property Indicators.
[src:united-states/united-states-p02] In 2025 the United States ranked third (after Switzerland and Sweden) in the Global Innovation Index.
[src:united-states/united-states-p02] The United States is considered to be a world leader in the development of artificial intelligence technology.
[src:united-states/united-states-p02] In 2023, the United States was ranked the second most technologically advanced country in the world (after South Korea) by *Global Finance* magazine.
[src:united-states/united-states-p02] The United States has maintained a space program since the late 1950s, beginning with the establishment of the National Aeronautics and Space Administration (NASA) in 1958.
[src:united-states/united-states-p02] In 1961, the United States became the second country (after the USSR) to successfully launch a human into space.
[src:united-states/united-states-p02] NASA's Apollo program (1961–1972) achieved the first crewed Moon landing with the 1969 Apollo 11 mission; it remains one of the agency's most significant milestones.
[src:united-states/united-states-p02] NASA is one of five agencies collaborating on the International Space Station (ISS); U.S. contributions to the ISS include several modules, including *Destiny* (2001), *Harmony* (2007), and *Tranquility* (2010), as well as ongoing logistical and operational support.
[src:united-states/united-states-p02] The United States private sector dominates the global commercial spaceflight industry.
[src:united-states/united-states-p02] Prominent American spaceflight contractors include Blue Origin, Boeing, Lockheed Martin, Northrop Grumman, and SpaceX.
[src:united-states/united-states-p02] NASA programs such as the Commercial Crew Program, Commercial Resupply Services, Commercial Lunar Payload Services, and NextSTEP have facilitated growing private-sector involvement in American spaceflight.
[src:united-states/united-states-p02] In 2023, the United States received approximately 84% of its energy from fossil fuel, and its largest source of energy was petroleum (38%), followed by natural gas (36%), renewable sources (9%), coal (9%), and nuclear power (9%).
[src:united-states/united-states-p02] In 2022, the United States constituted about 4% of the world's population, but consumed around 16% of the world's energy.
[src:united-states/united-states-p02] The U.S. ranks as the second-highest emitter of greenhouse gases behind China.
[src:united-states/united-states-p02] The U.S. is the world's largest producer of nuclear power, generating around 30% of the world's nuclear electricity.
[src:united-states/united-states-p02] It also has the highest number of nuclear power reactors of any country.
[src:united-states/united-states-p02] From 2024, the U.S. plans to triple its nuclear power capacity by 2050.
[src:united-states/united-states-p02] The United States' 4 million miles (6.4 million kilometers) of road network, owned almost entirely by state and local governments, is the longest in the world.
[src:united-states/united-states-p02] The extensive Interstate Highway System that connects all major U.S. cities is funded mostly by the federal government but maintained by state departments of transportation.
[src:united-states/united-states-p02] The system is further extended by state highways and some private toll roads.
[src:united-states/united-states-p02] The U.S. is among the top ten countries with the highest vehicle ownership per capita (850 vehicles per 1,000 people) in 2022.
[src:united-states/united-states-p02] A 2022 study found that 76% of U.S. commuters drive alone and 14% ride a bicycle, including bike owners and users of bike-sharing networks.
[src:united-states/united-states-p02] About 11% use some form of public transportation.
[src:united-states/united-states-p02] Public transportation in the United States is well developed in the largest urban areas, notably New York City, Washington, D.C., Boston, Philadelphia, Chicago, and San Francisco; otherwise, coverage is generally less extensive than in most other developed countries.
[src:united-states/united-states-p02] The U.S. also has many relatively car-dependent localities.
[src:united-states/united-states-p02] Long-distance intercity travel is provided primarily by airlines, but travel by rail is more common along the Northeast Corridor, where the only high-speed rail in the U.S. that meets international standards operates.
[src:united-states/united-states-p02] Amtrak, the country's government-sponsored national passenger rail company, has a relatively sparse network compared to that of Western European countries.
[src:united-states/united-states-p02] Service is concentrated in the Northeast, California, the Midwest, the Pacific Northwest, and Virginia/Southeast.
[src:united-states/united-states-p02] The country's rail transport network, the longest in the world at 182,412.3 mi (293,564.2 km), handles mostly freight (in contrast to more passenger-centered rail in Europe).
[src:united-states/united-states-p02] Because they are often privately owned operations, U.S. railroads lag behind those of the rest of the world in terms of electrification.
[src:united-states/united-states-p02] The United States has an extensive air transportation network.
[src:united-states/united-states-p02] U.S. civilian airlines are all privately owned.
[src:united-states/united-states-p02] The three largest airlines in the world, by total number of passengers carried, are U.S.-based; American Airlines became the global leader after its 2013 merger with US Airways.
[src:united-states/united-states-p02] Of the 50 busiest airports in the world, 16 are in the United States, as well as five of the top 10.
[src:united-states/united-states-p02] The world's busiest airport by passenger volume is Hartsfield–Jackson Atlanta International in Atlanta, Georgia.
[src:united-states/united-states-p02] In 2022, most of the 19,969 U.S. airports were owned and operated by local government authorities, and there are also some private airports.
[src:united-states/united-states-p02] Some 5,193 are designated as "public use", including for general aviation.
[src:united-states/united-states-p02] The Transportation Security Administration (TSA) has provided security at most major airports since 2001.
[src:united-states/united-states-p02] The country's inland waterways are the world's fifth-longest, totaling 25,482 mi (41,009 km).
[src:united-states/united-states-p02] They are used extensively for freight, recreation, and a small amount of passenger traffic.
[src:united-states/united-states-p02] Of the world's 50 busiest container ports, four are located in the United States, with the busiest in the country being the Port of Los Angeles.
[src:united-states/united-states-p02] Census Bureau reported 331,449,281 residents on April 1, 2020, making the United States the third-most-populous country in the world, after India and China.
[src:united-states/united-states-p02] The Census Bureau's official 2025 population estimate was 341,784,857, an increase of 3.1% since the 2020 census.
[src:united-states/united-states-p02] Population Clock, on July 1, 2024, the U.S. population had a net gain of one person every 16 seconds, or about 5400 people per day.
[src:united-states/united-states-p02] In 2023, 51% of Americans age 15 and over were married, 6% were widowed, 10% were divorced, and 34% had never been married.
[src:united-states/united-states-p02] In 2023, the total fertility rate for the U.S. stood at 1.6 children per woman, and, at 23%, it had the world's highest rate of children living in single-parent households in 2019.
[src:united-states/united-states-p02] Most Americans live in the suburbs of major metropolitan areas.
[src:united-states/united-states-p02] The United States has a diverse population; 37 ancestry groups have more than one million members.
[src:united-states/united-states-p02] White Americans with ancestry from Europe, the Middle East, or North Africa form the largest racial and ethnic group at 57.8% of the United States population.
[src:united-states/united-states-p02] Hispanic and Latino Americans form the second-largest group and are 18.7% of the United States population.
[src:united-states/united-states-p02] African Americans constitute the country's third-largest ancestry group and are 12.1% of the total U.S. population.
[src:united-states/united-states-p02] Asian Americans are the country's fourth-largest group, composing 5.9% of the United States population.
[src:united-states/united-states-p02] The country's 3.7 million Native Americans account for about 1%, and some 574 native tribes are recognized by the federal government.
[src:united-states/united-states-p02] In 2024, the median age of the United States population was 39.1 years.
[src:united-states/united-states-p02] About 82% of Americans live in metropolitan areas, particularly in suburbs and outer-ring exurbs; about half of those reside in cities with populations over 50,000.
[src:united-states/united-states-p02] In 2024, 346 incorporated U.S. municipalities had populations over 100,000, 11 cities had more than one million residents, and four cities—New York City, Los Angeles, Chicago, and Houston—had populations exceeding two million.
[src:united-states/united-states-p02] Some 56 U.S. metropolitan areas have one million or more residents.
[src:united-states/united-states-p02] More recently, the fastest-growing metropolitan areas were in the South, while southern metros along the Mexican border and Gulf Coast metros susceptible to hurricanes declined the most in 2025.
[src:united-states/united-states-p02] The New York metro area, which gained the most new residents in 2024, fell to 13th in 2025, due to a fall in immigrants.
[src:united-states/united-states-p02] The top metro areas with rising populations in 2025 were Houston and Dallas–Fort Worth, followed by Atlanta, Phoenix and Charlotte.
[src:united-states/united-states-p02] While many languages and dialects are spoken in the United States, English is by far the most commonly spoken and written.
[src:united-states/united-states-p02] *De facto*, English is the official language of the United States, and in 2025, Executive Order 14224 declared English official.
[src:united-states/united-states-p02] However, the U.S. has never had a statutory official language, as Congress has never passed a law to designate English as official for all three federal branches.
[src:united-states/united-states-p02] Some laws, such as U.S. naturalization requirements, nonetheless standardize English.
[src:united-states/united-states-p02] Twenty-eight states and the United States Virgin Islands have laws that designate English as the sole official language; 19 states and the District of Columbia have no official language.
[src:united-states/united-states-p02] In total, 169 Native American languages are spoken in the United States.
[src:united-states/united-states-p02] In Puerto Rico, Spanish is more widely spoken than English.
[src:united-states/united-states-p02] According to the American Community Survey (2020), some 245.4 million people in the U.S. age five and older spoke only English at home.
[src:united-states/united-states-p02] About 41.2 million spoke Spanish at home, making it the second most commonly used language.
[src:united-states/united-states-p02] Other languages spoken at home by one million people or more include Chinese (3.40 million), Tagalog (1.71 million), Vietnamese (1.52 million), Arabic (1.39 million), French (1.18 million), Korean (1.07 million), and Russian (1.04 million).
[src:united-states/united-states-p02] German, spoken by 1 million people at home in 2010, fell to 881,000 estimated total speakers in 2020.
[src:united-states/united-states-p02] America's immigrant population is by far the world's largest in absolute terms.
[src:united-states/united-states-p02] In 2022, there were 87.7 million immigrants and U.S.-born children of immigrants in the United States, accounting for nearly 27% of the overall U.S. population.
[src:united-states/united-states-p02] In 2017, out of the U.S. foreign-born population, some 45% (20.7 million) were naturalized citizens, 27% (12.3 million) were lawful permanent residents, 6% (2.2 million) were temporary lawful residents, and 23% (10.5 million) were unauthorized immigrants.
[src:united-states/united-states-p02] In 2019, the top countries of origin for immigrants were Mexico (24% of immigrants), India (6%), China (5%), the Philippines (4.5%), and El Salvador (3%).
[src:united-states/united-states-p02] In fiscal year 2022, over one million immigrants (most of whom entered through family reunification) were granted legal residence.
[src:united-states/united-states-p02] The undocumented immigrant population in the U.S. reached a record high of 14 million in 2023.
[src:united-states/united-states-p02] The First Amendment guarantees the free exercise of religion in the country and forbids Congress from passing laws respecting its establishment.
[src:united-states/united-states-p02] Religious practice is widespread, among the most diverse in the world, and profoundly vibrant.
[src:united-states/united-states-p02] The country has the world's largest Christian population, which includes the fourth-largest population of Catholics.
[src:united-states/united-states-p02] Other notable faiths include Judaism, Buddhism, Hinduism, Islam, New Age, and Native American religions.
[src:united-states/united-states-p02] Religious practice varies significantly by region.
[src:united-states/united-states-p02] "Ceremonial deism" is common in American culture.
[src:united-states/united-states-p02] The overwhelming majority of Americans believe in a higher power or spiritual force, engage in spiritual practices such as prayer, and consider themselves religious or spiritual.
[src:united-states/united-states-p02] In the Southern United States' "Bible Belt", evangelical Protestantism plays a significant role culturally; New England and the Western United States tend to be more secular.
[src:united-states/united-states-p02] Mormonism, a Restorationist movement founded in the U.S. in 1847, is the predominant religion in Utah and a major religion in Idaho.
[src:united-states/united-states-p02] According to the Centers for Disease Control and Prevention (CDC), average U.S. life expectancy at birth reached 79.0 years in 2024, its highest recorded level.
[src:united-states/united-states-p02] This was an increase of 0.6 years over 2023.
[src:united-states/united-states-p02] Starting in 1998, life expectancy in the U.S. fell behind that of other wealthy industrialized countries, and Americans' "health disadvantage" gap has been increasing ever since.
[src:united-states/united-states-p02] The Commonwealth Fund reported in 2020 that the U.S. had the highest suicide rate among high-income countries.
[src:united-states/united-states-p02] Approximately one-third of the U.S. adult population is obese, and another third is overweight.
[src:united-states/united-states-p02] The U.S. healthcare system far outspends that of any other country, measured both in per capita spending and as a percentage of GDP, but attains worse healthcare outcomes when compared to peer countries for reasons that are debated.
[src:united-states/united-states-p02] The United States is the only developed country without a system of universal healthcare, and a significant proportion of the population that does not carry health insurance.
[src:united-states/united-states-p02] Government-funded healthcare coverage for the poor (Medicaid) and for those age 65 and older (Medicare) is available to Americans who meet the programs' income or age qualifications.
[src:united-states/united-states-p02] In 2010, President Barack Obama passed the Patient Protection and Affordable Care Act.
[src:united-states/united-states-p02] Jackson Women's Health Organization*, which effectively overruled *Roe v.
[src:united-states/united-states-p02] Wade* (1973), abortion in the United States is no longer federally protected but is subject to the laws of each state or territory.
[src:united-states/united-states-p02] American primary and secondary education, known in the U.S. as K–12 ("kindergarten through 12th grade"), is decentralized.
[src:united-states/united-states-p02] School systems are operated by state, territorial, and sometimes municipal governments and regulated by the U.S.
[src:united-states/united-states-p02] In general, children are required to attend school or an approved homeschool from the age of five or six (kindergarten or first grade) until they are 18 years old.
[src:united-states/united-states-p02] This often brings students through the 12th grade, the final year of a U.S. high school, but some states and territories allow them to leave school earlier, at age 16 or 17.
[src:united-states/united-states-p02] The U.S. spends more on education per student than any other country, an average of $18,614 per year per public elementary and secondary school student in 2020–2021.
[src:united-states/united-states-p02] Among Americans age 25 and older, 92.2% graduated from high school, 62.7% attended some college, 37.7% earned a bachelor's degree, and 14.2% earned a graduate degree.
[src:united-states/united-states-p02] The U.S. literacy rate is near-universal.
[src:united-states/united-states-p02] The U.S. has produced the most Nobel Prize winners of any country, with 411 (having won 413 awards).
[src:united-states/united-states-p02] U.S. tertiary or higher education has earned a global reputation.
[src:united-states/united-states-p02] Many of the world's top universities, as listed by various ranking organizations, are in the United States, including 19 of the top 25.
[src:united-states/united-states-p02] American higher education is dominated by state university systems, although the country's many private universities and colleges enroll about 20% of all American students.
[src:united-states/united-states-p02] Local community colleges generally offer open admissions, lower tuition, and coursework leading to a two-year associate degree or a non-degree certificate.
[src:united-states/united-states-p02] As for public expenditures on higher education, the U.S. spends more per student than the OECD average, and Americans spend more than all nations in combined public and private spending.
[src:united-states/united-states-p02] Colleges and universities directly funded by the federal government do not charge tuition and are limited to military personnel and government employees, including: the U.S. service academies, the Naval Postgraduate School, and military staff colleges.
[src:united-states/united-states-p02] Despite some student loan forgiveness programs in place, student loan debt increased by 102% between 2010 and 2020, and exceeded $1.7 trillion in 2022.
[src:united-states/united-states-p03] The United States is home to a wide variety of ethnic groups, traditions, and customs.
[src:united-states/united-states-p03] The country has been described as having the values of individualism and personal autonomy, as well as a strong work ethic and competitiveness.
[src:united-states/united-states-p03] Voluntary altruism toward others also plays a major role; according to a 2016 study by the Charities Aid Foundation, Americans donated 1.44% of total GDP to charity—the highest rate in the world by a large margin.
[src:united-states/united-states-p03] Americans have traditionally been characterized by a unifying political belief in an "American Creed" in which emphasizes consent of the governed, liberty, equality under the law, democracy, social equality, property rights, and a preference for limited government.
[src:united-states/united-states-p03] The U.S. has acquired significant hard and soft power through its diplomatic influence, economic power, military alliances, and cultural exports such as American movies, music, video games, sports, and food.
[src:united-states/united-states-p03] The influence that the United States exerts on other countries through soft power is referred to as Americanization.
[src:united-states/united-states-p03] Nearly all present Americans or their ancestors came from Europe, Africa, or Asia (the "Old World") within the past five centuries.
[src:united-states/united-states-p03] Mainstream American culture is a Western culture largely derived from the traditions of European immigrants with influences from many other sources, such as traditions brought by slaves from Africa.
[src:united-states/united-states-p03] More recent immigration from Asia and especially Latin America has added to a cultural mix that has been described as a homogenizing melting pot, and a heterogeneous salad bowl, with immigrants contributing to, and often assimilating into, mainstream American culture.
[src:united-states/united-states-p03] Under the First Amendment to the Constitution, the United States is considered to have the strongest protections of free speech of any country.
[src:united-states/united-states-p03] Flag desecration, hate speech, blasphemy, and lese majesty are all forms of protected expression.
[src:united-states/united-states-p03] A 2016 Pew Research Center poll found that Americans were the most supportive of free expression of any polity measured.
[src:united-states/united-states-p03] Additionally, they are the "most supportive of freedom of the press and the right to use the Internet without government censorship".
[src:united-states/united-states-p03] The U.S. is a socially progressive country with permissive attitudes surrounding human sexuality.
[src:united-states/united-states-p03] LGBTQ rights in the United States are among the most advanced by global standards.
[src:united-states/united-states-p03] The American Dream, or the perception that Americans enjoy high levels of social mobility, plays a key role in attracting immigrants.
[src:united-states/united-states-p03] Whether this perception is accurate has been a topic of debate.
[src:united-states/united-states-p03] While mainstream culture holds that the United States is a classless society, scholars identify significant differences between the country's social classes, affecting socialization, language, and values.
[src:united-states/united-states-p03] Americans tend to greatly value socioeconomic achievement, but being ordinary or average is promoted by some as a noble condition as well.
[src:united-states/united-states-p03] Colonial American authors were influenced by John Locke and other Enlightenment philosophers.
[src:united-states/united-states-p03] The American Revolutionary Period (1765–1783) is notable for the political writings of Benjamin Franklin, Alexander Hamilton, Thomas Paine, and Thomas Jefferson.
[src:united-states/united-states-p03] Shortly before and after the Revolutionary War, the newspaper rose to prominence, filling a demand for anti-British national literature.
[src:united-states/united-states-p03] An early novel is William Hill Brown's *The Power of Sympathy*, published in 1791.
[src:united-states/united-states-p03] Ralph Waldo Emerson and Margaret Fuller pioneered the influential Transcendentalism movement; Henry David Thoreau, author of *Walden*, was influenced by this movement.
[src:united-states/united-states-p03] The conflict surrounding abolitionism inspired writers, like Harriet Beecher Stowe, and authors of slave narratives, such as Frederick Douglass.
[src:united-states/united-states-p03] Nathaniel Hawthorne's *The Scarlet Letter* (1850) explored the dark side of American history, as did Herman Melville's *Moby-Dick* (1851).
[src:united-states/united-states-p03] Major American poets of the 19th century American Renaissance include Walt Whitman, Melville, and Emily Dickinson.
[src:united-states/united-states-p03] Mark Twain was the first major American writer to be born in the West.
[src:united-states/united-states-p03] Henry James achieved international recognition with novels like *The Portrait of a Lady* (1881).
[src:united-states/united-states-p03] As literacy rates rose, periodicals published more stories centered around industrial workers, women, and the rural poor.
[src:united-states/united-states-p03] Naturalism, regionalism, and realism were the major literary movements of the period.
[src:united-states/united-states-p03] While modernism generally took on an international character, modernist authors working within the United States more often rooted their work in specific regions, peoples, and cultures.
[src:united-states/united-states-p03] Following the Great Migration to northern cities, African-American and black West Indian authors of the Harlem Renaissance developed an independent tradition of literature that rebuked a history of inequality and celebrated black culture.
[src:united-states/united-states-p03] An important cultural export during the Jazz Age, these writings were a key influence on *Négritude*, a philosophy emerging in the 1930s among francophone writers of the African diaspora.
[src:united-states/united-states-p03] In the 1950s, an ideal of homogeneity led many authors to attempt to write the Great American Novel, while the Beat Generation rejected this conformity, using styles that elevated the impact of the spoken word over mechanics to describe drug use, sexuality, and the failings of society.
[src:united-states/united-states-p03] Contemporary literature is more pluralistic than in previous eras, with the closest thing to a unifying feature being a trend toward self-conscious experiments with language.
[src:united-states/united-states-p03] Twelve American laureates have won the Nobel Prize in Literature.
[src:united-states/united-states-p03] The four major broadcasters in the U.S. are the National Broadcasting Company (NBC), Columbia Broadcasting System (CBS), American Broadcasting Company (ABC), and Fox Broadcasting Company (Fox).
[src:united-states/united-states-p03] The four major broadcast television networks are all commercial entities.
[src:united-states/united-states-p03] The Public Broadcasting Service (PBS) is the country's major non-commercial public broadcast network; it also provides educational programming through local PBS stations.
[src:united-states/united-states-p03] The U.S. cable television system offers hundreds of channels catering to a variety of niches.
[src:united-states/united-states-p03] In 2021, about 83% of Americans over age 12 listened to broadcast radio, while about 40% listened to podcasts.
[src:united-states/united-states-p03] In the prior year, there were 15,460 licensed full-power radio stations in the U.S. according to the Federal Communications Commission (FCC).
[src:united-states/united-states-p03] Public radio broadcasting is largely supplied by National Public Radio (NPR), incorporated in February 1970 under the Public Broadcasting Act of 1967.
[src:united-states/united-states-p03] U.S. newspapers with a global reach and reputation include *The Wall Street Journal*, *The New York Times*, *The Washington Post*, and *USA Today*.
[src:united-states/united-states-p03] About 800 publications are produced in Spanish.
[src:united-states/united-states-p03] With few exceptions, newspapers are privately owned, either by large chains such as Gannett or McClatchy, which own dozens or even hundreds of newspapers; by small chains that own a handful of papers; or, in an increasingly rare situation, by individuals or families.
[src:united-states/united-states-p03] Major cities often have alternative newspapers to complement the mainstream daily papers, such as *The Village Voice* in New York City and *LA Weekly* in Los Angeles.
[src:united-states/united-states-p03] The five most-visited websites in the world are Google, YouTube, Facebook, Instagram, and ChatGPT—all of them American-owned.
[src:united-states/united-states-p03] Other popular platforms used include X (formerly Twitter) and Amazon.
[src:united-states/united-states-p03] In 2025, the U.S. was the world's second-largest video game market by revenue (after China).
[src:united-states/united-states-p03] In 2015, the U.S. video game industry consisted of 2,457 companies that employed around 220,000 jobs and generated $30.4 billion in revenue.
[src:united-states/united-states-p03] There are 444 game publishers, developers, and hardware companies in California alone.
[src:united-states/united-states-p03] According to the Game Developers Conference (GDC), the U.S. is the top location for video game development, with 58% of the world's game developers based there in 2025.
[src:united-states/united-states-p03] Media freedom was classified as "problematic" by Reporters Without Borders in 2026, and scholars have noted a significant rise in censorship and self-censorship in recent years.
[src:united-states/united-states-p03] The United States is well known for its theater.
[src:united-states/united-states-p03] Mainstream theater in the United States derives from the old European theatrical tradition and has been heavily influenced by the British theater.
[src:united-states/united-states-p03] By the middle of the 19th century, America had created new distinct dramatic forms in the Tom Shows, the showboat theater and the minstrel show.
[src:united-states/united-states-p03] The central hub of the American theater scene is the Theater District in Manhattan, with its divisions of Broadway, off-Broadway, and off-off-Broadway.
[src:united-states/united-states-p03] Many movie and television celebrities have gotten their big break working in New York productions.
[src:united-states/united-states-p03] Outside New York City, many cities have professional regional or resident theater companies that produce their own seasons.
[src:united-states/united-states-p03] The biggest-budget theatrical productions are musicals.
[src:united-states/united-states-p03] U.S. theater has an active community theater culture.
[src:united-states/united-states-p03] The Tony Awards recognize excellence in live Broadway theater and are presented at an annual ceremony in Manhattan.
[src:united-states/united-states-p03] The awards are given for Broadway productions and performances.
[src:united-states/united-states-p03] Folk art in colonial America grew out of artisanal craftsmanship in communities that allowed commonly trained people to individually express themselves.
[src:united-states/united-states-p03] It was distinct from Europe's tradition of high art, which was less accessible and generally less relevant to early American settlers.
[src:united-states/united-states-p03] Cultural movements in art and craftsmanship in colonial America generally lagged behind those of Western Europe.
[src:united-states/united-states-p03] For example, the prevailing medieval style of woodworking and primitive sculpture became integral to early American folk art, despite the emergence of Renaissance styles in England in the late 16th and early 17th centuries.
[src:united-states/united-states-p03] The new English styles would have been early enough to make a considerable impact on American folk art, but American styles and forms had already been firmly adopted.
[src:united-states/united-states-p03] Not only did styles change slowly in early America, but there was a tendency for rural artisans there to continue their traditional forms longer than their urban counterparts did—and far longer than those in Western Europe.
[src:united-states/united-states-p03] The Hudson River School was a mid-19th-century movement in the visual arts tradition of European naturalism.
[src:united-states/united-states-p03] The 1913 Armory Show in New York City, an exhibition of European modernist art, shocked the public and transformed the U.S. art scene.
[src:united-states/united-states-p03] American Realism and American Regionalism sought to reflect and give America new ways of looking at itself.
[src:united-states/united-states-p03] Georgia O'Keeffe, Marsden Hartley, and others experimented with new and individualistic styles, which would become known as American modernism.
[src:united-states/united-states-p03] Major artistic movements such as the abstract expressionism of Jackson Pollock and Willem de Kooning and the pop art of Andy Warhol and Roy Lichtenstein developed largely in the United States.
[src:united-states/united-states-p03] Major photographers include Alfred Stieglitz, Edward Steichen, Dorothea Lange, Edward Weston, James Van Der Zee, Ansel Adams, and Gordon Parks.
[src:united-states/united-states-p03] The tide of modernism and then postmodernism has brought global fame to American architects, including Frank Lloyd Wright, Philip Johnson, and Frank Gehry.
[src:united-states/united-states-p03] The Metropolitan Museum of Art in Manhattan is the largest art museum in the United States and the fourth-largest in the world.
[src:united-states/united-states-p03] American folk music encompasses numerous music genres, variously known as traditional music, traditional folk music, contemporary folk music, or roots music.
[src:united-states/united-states-p03] Many traditional songs have been sung within the same family or folk group for generations, and sometimes trace back to such origins as the British Isles, mainland Europe, or Africa.
[src:united-states/united-states-p03] The rhythmic and lyrical styles of African-American music in particular have influenced American music.
[src:united-states/united-states-p03] Banjos were brought to America through the slave trade.
[src:united-states/united-states-p03] Minstrel shows incorporating the instrument into their acts led to its increased popularity and widespread production in the 19th century.
[src:united-states/united-states-p03] The electric guitar, first invented in the 1930s, and mass-produced by the 1940s, had an enormous influence on popular music, in particular due to the development of rock and roll.
[src:united-states/united-states-p03] The synthesizer, turntablism, and electronic music were also largely developed in the U.S.
[src:united-states/united-states-p03] Elements from folk idioms such as the blues and old-time music were adopted and transformed into popular genres with global audiences.
[src:united-states/united-states-p03] Jazz grew from blues and ragtime in the early 20th century, developing from the innovations and recordings of composers such as W.C.
[src:united-states/united-states-p03] Louis Armstrong and Duke Ellington increased its popularity early in the 20th century.
[src:united-states/united-states-p03] Country music developed in the 1920s, bluegrass and rhythm and blues in the 1940s, and rock and roll in the 1950s.
[src:united-states/united-states-p03] In the 1960s, Bob Dylan emerged from the folk revival to become one of the country's most celebrated songwriters.
[src:united-states/united-states-p03] The musical forms of punk and hip hop both originated in the United States in the 1970s.
[src:united-states/united-states-p03] The United States has the world's largest music market, with a total retail value of $15.9 billion in 2022, and is the largest exporter of music.
[src:united-states/united-states-p03] Most of the world's major record companies are based in the U.S.; they are represented by the Recording Industry Association of America (RIAA).
[src:united-states/united-states-p03] The United States has the world's largest apparel market by revenue.
[src:united-states/united-states-p03] Apart from professional business attire, American fashion is eclectic and predominantly informal.
[src:united-states/united-states-p03] Americans' diverse cultural roots are reflected in their clothing; however, sneakers, jeans, T-shirts, and baseball caps are emblematic of American styles.
[src:united-states/united-states-p03] New York, with its Fashion Week, is considered to be one of the "Big Four" global fashion capitals, along with Paris, Milan, and London.
[src:united-states/united-states-p03] A study demonstrated that general proximity to Manhattan's Garment District has been synonymous with American fashion since its inception in the early 20th century.
[src:united-states/united-states-p03] A number of well-known designer labels, among them Tommy Hilfiger, Ralph Lauren, Tom Ford and Calvin Klein, are headquartered in Manhattan.
[src:united-states/united-states-p03] Labels cater to niche markets, such as preteens.
[src:united-states/united-states-p03] New York Fashion Week is one of the most influential fashion shows in the world, and is held twice each year in Manhattan; the annual Met Gala, also in Manhattan, has been called the fashion world's "biggest night".
[src:united-states/united-states-p03] The U.S. film industry has a worldwide influence and following.
[src:united-states/united-states-p03] Hollywood, a district in central Los Angeles, the nation's second-most populous city, is also metonymous for the American filmmaking industry.
[src:united-states/united-states-p03] The major film studios of the United States are the primary source of the most commercially successful movies selling the most tickets in the world.
[src:united-states/united-states-p03] Largely centered in the New York City region from its beginnings in the late 19th century through the first decades of the 20th century, the U.S. film industry has since been primarily based in and around Hollywood.
[src:united-states/united-states-p03] Nonetheless, American film companies have been subject to the forces of globalization in the 21st century, and an increasing number of films are made elsewhere.
[src:united-states/united-states-p03] The Academy Awards, popularly known as "the Oscars", have been held annually by the Academy of Motion Picture Arts and Sciences since 1929, and the Golden Globes have been held annually since January 1944.
[src:united-states/united-states-p03] The industry peaked in what is commonly referred to as the "Golden Age of Hollywood", from the early sound period until the early 1960s, with screen actors such as John Wayne and Marilyn Monroe becoming iconic figures.
[src:united-states/united-states-p03] In the 1970s, "New Hollywood", or the "Hollywood Renaissance", was defined by grittier films influenced by French and Italian realist pictures of the post-war period.
[src:united-states/united-states-p03] The 21st century has been marked by the rise of American streaming platforms, which came to rival traditional cinema.
[src:united-states/united-states-p03] Early settlers were introduced by Native Americans to foods such as turkey, sweet potatoes, corn, squash, and maple syrup.
[src:united-states/united-states-p03] Of the most enduring and pervasive examples are variations of the native dish called succotash.
[src:united-states/united-states-p03] Early settlers and later immigrants combined these with foods they were familiar with, such as wheat flour, beef, and milk, to create a distinctive American cuisine.
[src:united-states/united-states-p03] New World crops, especially pumpkin, corn, potatoes, and turkey as the main course are part of a shared national menu on Thanksgiving, when many Americans prepare or purchase traditional dishes to celebrate the occasion.
[src:united-states/united-states-p03] Characteristic American dishes such as apple pie, fried chicken, doughnuts, french fries, macaroni and cheese, ice cream, hamburgers, hot dogs, and American pizza derive from the recipes of various immigrant groups.
[src:united-states/united-states-p03] Mexican dishes such as burritos and tacos preexisted the United States in areas later annexed from Mexico, and adaptations of Chinese cuisine as well as pasta dishes freely adapted from Italian sources are all widely consumed.
[src:united-states/united-states-p03] American chefs have had a significant impact on society both domestically and internationally.
[src:united-states/united-states-p03] In 1946, the Culinary Institute of America was founded by Katharine Angell and Frances Roth.
[src:united-states/united-states-p03] This would become the United States' most prestigious culinary school, where many of the most talented American chefs would study prior to successful careers.
[src:united-states/united-states-p03] The United States restaurant industry was projected at $899 billion in sales for 2020, and employed more than 15 million people, representing 10% of the nation's workforce directly.
[src:united-states/united-states-p03] It is the country's second-largest private employer and the third-largest employer overall.
[src:united-states/united-states-p03] The United States is home to over 220 Michelin-starred restaurants, 14 of which were awarded three stars.
[src:united-states/united-states-p03] Wine has been produced in what is now the United States since the 1500s, with the first widespread production beginning in what is now New Mexico in 1628.
[src:united-states/united-states-p03] In the modern U.S., wine production is undertaken in all fifty states, with California producing 84 percent of all U.S. wine.
[src:united-states/united-states-p03] With more than 1,100,000 acres (4,500 km2) under vine, the United States is the fourth-largest wine-producing country in the world, after Italy, Spain, and France.
[src:united-states/united-states-p03] The classic American diner, a casual restaurant type originally intended for the working class, emerged during the 19th century from converted railroad dining cars made stationary.
[src:united-states/united-states-p03] The diner soon evolved into purpose-built structures whose number expanded greatly in the 20th century.
[src:united-states/united-states-p03] The American fast-food industry developed alongside the nation's car culture.
[src:united-states/united-states-p03] American restaurants developed the drive-in format in the 1920s, which they began to replace with the drive-through format by the 1940s.
[src:united-states/united-states-p03] American fast-food restaurant chains, such as McDonald's, Burger King, Chick-fil-A, Kentucky Fried Chicken, Dunkin' Donuts and many others, have numerous outlets around the world.
[src:united-states/united-states-p03] The most popular spectator sports in the U.S. are American football, basketball, baseball, soccer, and ice hockey.
[src:united-states/united-states-p03] While most major U.S. sports such as baseball and American football have evolved out of European practices, basketball, volleyball, skateboarding, and snowboarding are American inventions, many of which have become popular worldwide.
[src:united-states/united-states-p03] Lacrosse and surfing arose from Native American and Native Hawaiian activities that predate European contact.
[src:united-states/united-states-p03] The market for professional sports in the United States was approximately $69 billion in July 2013, roughly 50% larger than that of Europe, the Middle East, and Africa combined.
[src:united-states/united-states-p03] Professional wrestling was widely popularized in the country, with the United States serving as the home country for World Wrestling Entertainment and All Elite Wrestling, the two largest wrestling promotions in the world.
[src:united-states/united-states-p03] American football is by several measures the most popular spectator sport in the United States.
[src:united-states/united-states-p03] Although American football does not have a substantial following in other nations, the NFL does have the highest average attendance (67,254) of any professional sports league in the world.
[src:united-states/united-states-p03] In the year 2024, the NFL generated over $23 billion, making it the most valued professional sports league in the United States and the world.
[src:united-states/united-states-p03] "national sport" since the late 19th century.
[src:united-states/united-states-p03] The most-watched individual sports in the U.S. are golf and auto racing, particularly NASCAR and IndyCar.
[src:united-states/united-states-p03] On the collegiate level, earnings for the member institutions exceed $1 billion annually, and college football and basketball attract large audiences, as the NCAA March Madness tournament and the College Football Playoff are some of the most watched national sporting events.
[src:united-states/united-states-p03] In the U.S., the intercollegiate sports level serves as the main feeder system for professional and Olympic sports, with significant exceptions such as Minor League Baseball.
[src:united-states/united-states-p03] This differs greatly from practices in nearly all other countries, where publicly and privately funded sports organizations serve this function.
[src:united-states/united-states-p03] Eight Olympic Games have taken place in the United States.
[src:united-states/united-states-p03] Louis, Missouri, were the first-ever Olympic Games held outside of Europe.
[src:united-states/united-states-p03] The Olympic Games will be held in the U.S. for a ninth time when Los Angeles hosts the 2028 Summer Olympics.
[src:united-states/united-states-p03] U.S. athletes have won a total of 2,968 medals (1,179 gold) at the Olympic Games, the most of any country.
[src:united-states/united-states-p03] In other international competition, the United States is the home of a number of prestigious events, including the America's Cup, World Baseball Classic, the U.S.
[src:united-states/united-states-p03] The U.S. men's national soccer team has qualified for eleven World Cups, while the women's national team has won the FIFA Women's World Cup and Olympic soccer tournament four and five times, respectively.
[src:united-states/united-states-p03] The 1999 FIFA Women's World Cup was hosted by the United States.
[src:united-states/united-states-p03] Its final match was attended by 90,185, setting the world record for largest women's sporting event crowd at the time.
[src:united-states/united-states-p03] The United States hosted the 1994 FIFA World Cup and is currently co-hosting, along with Canada and Mexico, the 2026 FIFA World Cup.
[src:united-states/us] The *us* domain is less commonly used by American businesses and enterprises than the internationally more common *.com*.
[src:united-states/us] On February 15, 1985, *us* was created as the Internet's first ccTLD.
[src:united-states/us] Its original administrator was Jon Postel of the Information Sciences Institute (ISI) at the University of Southern California (USC).
[src:united-states/us] He administered *us* under a subcontract that the ISI and USC had from SRI International (which held the *us* and the gTLD contract with the United States Department of Defense) and later Network Solutions (which held the *us* and the gTLD contract with the National Science Foundation).
[src:united-states/us] Postel and his colleague Ann Westine Cooper codified the *us* ccTLD's policies in December 1992 as RFC 1386 and revised them the following June in RFC 1480.
[src:united-states/us] Registrants could only register third-level domains or higher in a geographic and organizational hierarchy.
[src:united-states/us] From June 1993 to June 1997, Postel delegated the vast majority of the geographic subdomains under *us* to various public and private entities.
[src:united-states/us] *us* registrants could register with the delegated manager for the specific zone they wished to register in, but not directly with the *us* administrator.
[src:united-states/us] In July 1997, Postel instituted a "50/500 rule" that limited each delegated manager to 500 localities maximum, 50 in a given state.
[src:united-states/us] In June 1998, Postel raised the possibility of covering IANA operating costs by charging locality name registrars, who would pass the costs along to individual registrants.
[src:united-states/us] In September 1998, the United States Postal Service proposed funding the operations in order to assume control of *us*, as part of a plan to diversify away from postage revenue.
[src:united-states/us] On October 1, 1998, the NSF transferred oversight of the *us* domain to the National Telecommunications and Information Administration (NTIA) of the United States Department of Commerce.
[src:united-states/us] Postel died that month, leaving his domain administration responsibilities with ISI.
[src:united-states/us] In December 2000, these responsibilities were transferred to Network Solutions, which had recently been acquired by Verisign.
[src:united-states/us] On October 26, 2001, Neustar was awarded the contract to administer *us*.
[src:united-states/us] On April 24, 2002, second-level domains under *us* became available for registration.
[src:united-states/us] One of the first *us* domain hacks, icio.us, was registered on May 3, 2002, for the creation of the subdomain del.icio.us.
[src:united-states/us] A moratorium was placed on additional delegations of locality-based namespaces, and Neustar became the default delegate for undelegated localities.
[src:united-states/us] Neustar's contract was renewed by the National Telecommunications and Information Administration (NTIA) in 2007, 2014, and most recently in 2019 for a term of 10 years.
[src:united-states/us] On March 31, 2019, the *us* registry made it clear that under its Acceptable Use Policy it would not allow the sale of opioids through the *us* top level domain.
[src:united-states/us] In Q2 2020, GoDaddy acquired Neustar's registry business.
[src:united-states/us] The *us* ccTLD is historically organized under a complex *locality namespace* hierarchy.
[src:united-states/us] Until second-level registrations were introduced in 2002, *us* permitted only fourth-level domain registrations of the form *organization-name*.*locality*.*state*.us, with some exceptions for government entities.
[src:united-states/us] Registrants of locality-based domains must meet the same criteria as in the rest of the *us* ccTLD.
[src:united-states/us] Though the locality namespace is most commonly used for government entities, it is also open to registrations by private businesses and individuals.
[src:united-states/us] Since 2002, second-level domain registrations have eclipsed those in the locality namespace, and many local governments have transitioned to .org and other TLDs.
[src:united-states/us] In the 2010s, the first top-level domains for U.S. cities became available as paid alternatives to third-level locality domains, including .nyc as an alternative to .new-york.ny.us.
[src:united-states/us] Many locality-based zones of *us* are delegated to various public and private entities known as *delegated managers*.
[src:united-states/us] Domains in these zones are registered through the delegated manager, rather than through GoDaddy.
[src:united-states/us] As the delegated managers are expected to receive requests directly from registrants, few if any domain name registrars serve this space, possibly contributing to its lower visibility and utilization.
[src:united-states/us] This hierarchical system has proven unappealing to companies that operate nationally or globally.
[src:united-states/us] As of October 31, 2013, 12,979 domains were registered under the locality namespace, of which 3,653 were managed by about 1,300 delegated managers while 9,326 were managed by Neustar as the *de facto* manager.
[src:united-states/us] According to a 2013 survey of 539 delegated managers, 282 were state or local government agencies, while 98 were private individuals and 85 were commercial Internet service providers.
[src:united-states/us] Nearly 90% of the respondents offer domain registrations for free.
[src:united-states/us] The .au and .ca ccTLDs have also established third- and fourth-level locality namespaces, though the .ca locality namespace is no longer open to registrations.
[src:united-states/us] The .cn ccTLD maintains a third-level locality namespace in general use.
[src:united-states/us] A two-letter second-level domain is formally reserved for each U.S. state, federal territory, and the District of Columbia.
[src:united-states/us] Each domain corresponds to a USPS abbreviation.
[src:united-states/us] For example, .ny.us is reserved for websites affiliated with New York, while .va.us is for those affiliated with Virginia.
[src:united-states/us] Second-level domains are also reserved for five U.S. territories: .as.us for American Samoa, .gu.us for Guam, .mp.us for the Northern Mariana Islands, .pr.us for Puerto Rico, and .vi.us for the U.S.
[src:united-states/us] However, these domains go unused because each territory has its own ccTLD per ISO 3166-1 alpha-2: respectively, .as, .gu, .mp, .pr, and .vi.
[src:united-states/us] A state's main government portal is usually found at the third-level domain state.*state*.us, which is reserved for this purpose.
[src:united-states/us] However, some state administrations prefer .gov domains: for example, California's government portal is located at www.ca.gov.
[src:united-states/us] Other than for state governments, no third-level domain registrations are permitted under state or territory second-level domains.
[src:united-states/us] A large number of third-level domains are reserved for localities within states.
[src:united-states/us] Each fourth-level domain registration under this namespace follows the format *organization-name*.*locality*.*state*.us, where *state* is a state's two-letter postal abbreviation and *locality* is a hyphenated name that corresponds to a ZIP code or appears in a well-known atlas.
[src:united-states/us] In some cases, a local government that serves as the delegated manager for its own locality may locate its website directly under the *locality*, omitting the *organization-name*.
[src:united-states/us] For example, the website of the City of Brunswick, Ohio, is located at www.brunswick.oh.us rather than www.ci.brunswick.oh.us, and the website of Delhi Township, Ohio, is located at www.delhi.oh.us instead of www.twp.delhi.oh.us.
[src:united-states/us] Unusually, Lima, Ohio, is located at www.cityhall.lima.oh.us.
[src:united-states/us] Many large cities use .gov extensions, for example Chicago (www.chicago.gov); Rochester, New York and (www.cityofrochester.gov).
[src:united-states/us] Several cities, villages, and towns use the *locality**state*.gov format, often with the state abbreviated, for example, Atlanta, Georgia (www.atlantaga.gov), Northport, New York (www.northportny.gov), and Huntington, New York (www.huntingtonny.gov).
[src:united-states/us] Although most New York City websites have moved to www.nyc.gov, *us* redirects exist for individual city agencies, such as the Independent Budget Office at www.ibo.nyc.ny.us and the Board of Elections at vote.nyc.ny.us.
[src:united-states/us] The *us* TLD registrar serves as the default delegated manager for all undelegated third-level locality domains, as well as any locality domains relinquished by delegated managers.
[src:united-states/us] Under Neustar and GoDaddy, the registrar has discontinued delegation of third-level locality domains, as well as registration of domain names under any locality or affinity domain for which it serves as the delegated manager.
[src:united-states/us] Some delegated managers alternatively register domains under common abbreviations of locality names, which are not necessarily interchangeable.
[src:united-states/us] Many of these abbreviations came from Western Union's "City Mnemonics" list.
[src:united-states/us] Some of these affinity namespaces have been supplanted by more convenient sponsored top-level domains.
[src:united-states/us] The first sTLD, .museum, became available in October 2001 as an alternative to the .mus namespace.
[src:united-states/us] Since April 2003, the .edu top-level domain has been available as an alternative for community colleges, technical and vocational schools, and other tertiary educational institutions that might have previously used the .cc or .tec affinity namespaces.
[src:united-states/us] Although the Kentucky Department of Education operates the .k12.ky.us namespace for Kentucky school districts, most districts instead use subdomains of the less formal domain kyschools.us, which the department operates in a similar manner.
[src:united-states/us] For example, Gallatin county schools have a website at www.gallatin.k12.ky.us, while Paducah Public Schools are located at paducah.kyschools.us and the McCracken County Public Schools use mccracken.kyschools.us as a redirect to www.mccrackencountyschools.net.
[src:united-states/us] The Dot Kids Implementation and Efficiency Act of 2002 (Pub.
[src:united-states/us] 107–317 (text) (PDF)) established a *.kids.us* second-level domain.
[src:united-states/us] The general public could register third-level domains under *.kids.us* for educational content that met strict requirements, including conformance to the Children's Online Privacy Protection Act and adherence to Children's Advertising Review Unit standards.
[src:united-states/us] Webpages were prohibited from linking outside the *.kids.us* namespace.
[src:united-states/us] On July 27, 2012, in response to declining usage and a petition by Neustar the previous year, the NTIA suspended *.kids.us* registrations.
[src:united-states/us] By that time, 651 domains were registered under *.kids.us*, and only five registrants (Nickelodeon, Nick Jr., PBS Kids, the Smithsonian Center for Education and Museum Studies, and Super-Fun Sports Inc., operating trampoline.kids.us and trampolines.kids.us) were operating active websites.
[src:united-states/us] To ensure that these requirements are met, GoDaddy frequently conducts "spot checks" on registrant information.
[src:united-states/us] Registrants are required to provide complete contact information without omissions.
[src:united-states/us] Under the locality namespace, delegated managers may impose additional requirements.
[src:united-states/us] For example, the former Texas Regional Hostmaster restricted each of its delegated localities to organizations that had a mailing address in that locality.
[src:united-states/us] Some sponsored top-level domains (sTLDs) are restricted to U.S.-based entities, other than some grandfathered registrations.
[src:united-states/us] These domains are much more popular than the equivalent domains under *us*.
[src:united-states/us] Territories of the United States use their own country code top-level domains (ccTLDs).
[src:united-states/us] Identical domains are reserved under *us* but in practice go unused.
[src:united-states/us] Some U.S. cities are the focus of generic top-level domains under the New gTLD Program.
[src:united-states/us] These gTLDs are not necessarily affiliated with the delegated managers of the corresponding third-level domains within the *us* locality namespace.
[src:united-states/us] Unofficially, some ccTLDs belonging to other countries are used by U.S.-based private organizations and state government agencies based on their similarity to postal state abbreviations or informal city name abbreviations.
